WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:50.350 --> 00:00:51.479
[Western  music]

00:00:55.810 --> 00:00:58.309
[Peter] Good morning
from Southwest Colorado.

00:00:58.376 --> 00:01:02.754
a part of the country
where things change very fast economically.

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:06.471
So today we got
a great road trip starting here

00:01:07.128 --> 00:01:11.005
in the ranching outpost of Cortez
on the edge of the desert

00:01:11.605 --> 00:01:14.311
and going into
the high mountains of Telluride.

00:01:14.951 --> 00:01:17.810
One of the wealthiest towns in the country

00:01:18.273 --> 00:01:20.631
where the median sale price of a home

00:01:21.206 --> 00:01:25.032
is currently $4.7 million.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:29.083
We have Arizona,
New Mexico right down there.

00:01:29.150 --> 00:01:30.830
The four corners region.

00:01:30.897 --> 00:01:32.956
Also Utah right over the mountains.

00:01:33.383 --> 00:01:36.846
And this is Cortez.
The outskirts of Cortez.

00:01:37.264 --> 00:01:40.814
Got some of those
old ranching homes out there.

00:01:40.881 --> 00:01:42.976
And you can see the scrub brush.

00:01:43.043 --> 00:01:44.339
Small junipers.

00:01:44.973 --> 00:01:46.072
High desert.

00:01:46.139 --> 00:01:48.781
But in just under 100 miles

00:01:48.848 --> 00:01:51.495
we're gonna be in
completely different worlds.

00:01:53.051 --> 00:01:54.110
How you doing, sir?

00:01:54.815 --> 00:01:57.315
Maybe do some advertising
on these flower planters.

00:01:57.382 --> 00:01:58.536
-What are you doing?

00:01:58.603 --> 00:02:01.439
-Well this is some of the stuff I build.
-Oh nice.

00:02:01.506 --> 00:02:02.949
-So these planters.
-Yeah.

00:02:03.016 --> 00:02:06.644
You were saying off camera you want me
to tell the Telluride people…

00:02:06.711 --> 00:02:08.400
-…that you're selling planters?
-Exactly.

00:02:08.467 --> 00:02:10.412
They can find me in Cortez. [laughs]

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:12.045
-Just come here. Okay.

00:02:13.715 --> 00:02:15.668
Here's some of the things I do.

00:02:15.735 --> 00:02:17.676
Only because I am a musician too.

00:02:18.468 --> 00:02:19.351
Oh nice.

00:02:20.207 --> 00:02:24.113
-Cool wall guitar. How much are these?
-I'm trying to get 20 bucks a piece.

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:25.577
Oh that's totally fair.

00:02:25.644 --> 00:02:27.800
-You lived here all your life?
-Pretty much.

00:02:27.867 --> 00:02:30.324
-This is your place?
-Yeah this is my RV.

00:02:30.391 --> 00:02:33.663
Well one of the oldest
trailer parks in Cortez.

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:37.486
-You keep it tight though. It looks clean.
-That's all Ute Reservation.

00:02:37.553 --> 00:02:39.373
You got Mesa Verde National Park.

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:41.695
It's a gateway
to Rocky Mountains basically.

00:02:41.762 --> 00:02:43.438
-How you doing sir?
-Good. You?

00:02:43.505 --> 00:02:44.917
Good. Do you know Kelly?

00:02:45.482 --> 00:02:47.137
-Yeah.
-Yeah we know each other.

00:02:47.204 --> 00:02:48.702
How's it out here these days?

00:02:48.769 --> 00:02:52.050
This town was settled way out
in the middle of nothing.

00:02:52.117 --> 00:02:55.316
And as you go through it
this has always been a Native…

00:02:55.383 --> 00:02:58.716
You have two Native tribes
that are literally fighting

00:02:59.115 --> 00:03:02.321
over the property or the land
right below this town.

00:03:02.749 --> 00:03:05.709
What I feel and what I've seen,
this town has coexisted.

00:03:05.776 --> 00:03:08.188
Everybody worked together for a long time.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:11.959
Everything. They've tried to
educate everybody on the same level.

00:03:12.026 --> 00:03:14.054
They've tried to bring everything down.

00:03:14.121 --> 00:03:17.074
But when you get to
the point of where we are today…

00:03:17.141 --> 00:03:18.123
Uh-huh.

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:19.249
There's a problem.

00:03:19.700 --> 00:03:21.380
I don't know what the problem is.

00:03:21.447 --> 00:03:22.565
With the education?

00:03:23.412 --> 00:03:27.140
I'm saying with everything, not just
education, society, it's everything.

00:03:27.207 --> 00:03:30.736
When we were brought up
we were taught to respect our elders.

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:34.252
We were taught that
there was a moral standard in the world.

00:03:34.319 --> 00:03:36.778
A lot of kids at the time when I was a kid,

00:03:36.845 --> 00:03:38.963
I'm assuming same as you in your age,

00:03:39.563 --> 00:03:42.092
our parents had guns
in the back of our car.

00:03:42.666 --> 00:03:45.284
I was taught how to use a gun way young.

00:03:45.671 --> 00:03:48.154
And was taught how to use it respectfully.

00:03:48.221 --> 00:03:51.289
We had gun racks in our pickups
when we went to high school.

00:03:51.356 --> 00:03:53.022
-You can't do that anymore right?

00:03:53.089 --> 00:03:56.696
No you can't. And there's a reason
because there's a lot of individuals

00:03:56.763 --> 00:04:01.474
when this punk culture and when I say
punk culture I don't mean punk rock.

00:04:01.548 --> 00:04:05.181
I mean the pranksters that are
coming up and going, "It's just a prank."

00:04:05.248 --> 00:04:06.596
-It's a lack of respect.

00:04:06.663 --> 00:04:08.776
That too. That goes along with it.

00:04:08.843 --> 00:04:11.404
Causing trouble.
They literally walk into a store

00:04:11.471 --> 00:04:14.382
and they belittle somebody
just to see their reaction

00:04:14.449 --> 00:04:16.866
and then come back with
"Oh, it's just a prank."

00:04:16.933 --> 00:04:18.629
Isn't that from the parenting though?

00:04:18.696 --> 00:04:20.488
It could be. It could be.

00:04:20.555 --> 00:04:22.961
-Well what happened is

00:04:23.028 --> 00:04:26.382
they changed the law
where you couldn't discipline your kid.

00:04:26.449 --> 00:04:29.496
When I was growing up,
you did something that was out of line,

00:04:29.563 --> 00:04:31.113
your dad would bust your a**.

00:04:31.180 --> 00:04:34.750
-[Peter] Yeah. I didn't cross my father.
-And that was discipline.

00:04:34.817 --> 00:04:38.021
If somehow we could get
the United States to go back.

00:04:38.506 --> 00:04:42.153
And I say this very loosely
'cause I don't want to go into this

00:04:42.801 --> 00:04:44.275
bigotry all that other stuff.

00:04:44.342 --> 00:04:46.553
-There's a lot of
frustration in the country.

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:51.149
-Exactly. If we can go back to the sixties,
seventies, eighties, and nineties,

00:04:51.216 --> 00:04:54.510
when people were more involved
with helping and being in love

00:04:54.577 --> 00:04:56.216
and being tight with each other

00:04:56.283 --> 00:04:58.812
and understanding
and respecting everybody's

00:04:59.568 --> 00:05:00.922
bubble so to speak,

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:02.779
It'd be a lot easier.

00:05:03.225 --> 00:05:06.562
But right now everybody's
been taught and perceived

00:05:06.636 --> 00:05:09.988
that it's okay to be who you are.
It makes no difference.

00:05:10.477 --> 00:05:13.663
Now we have children
that are literally walking down the street

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:15.545
going, "I'm 17 years old."

00:05:15.612 --> 00:05:18.920
They don't have it in mind that
they could be charged for something

00:05:18.987 --> 00:05:21.662
but they're going,
"I'm 17 years old. I'm still a kid.

00:05:21.729 --> 00:05:24.429
There's nothing
you can do about me." from 12 up.

00:05:24.496 --> 00:05:27.089
-What about crime here in Cortez?
Is there much?

00:05:27.156 --> 00:05:29.226
-I can't answer that.
-It's getting worse.

00:05:29.293 --> 00:05:31.406
But around here it's pretty safe, right?

00:05:31.473 --> 00:05:32.606
-Well yeah.

00:05:32.673 --> 00:05:35.001
-You watch out for each other?
-This is a neighborhood.

00:05:35.068 --> 00:05:36.535
You guys all know each other?

00:05:36.602 --> 00:05:41.170
You got people like me, if I catch somebody
doing something stupid I'll go at them.

00:05:41.890 --> 00:05:43.211
Simple as that.

00:05:43.278 --> 00:05:45.638
-The one thing I can say about Coloradoans

00:05:45.705 --> 00:05:46.588
[Peter] Yeah…

00:05:46.991 --> 00:05:49.119
We're a family-orientated state.

00:05:49.778 --> 00:05:51.903
They will hurt, they will fight,

00:05:52.723 --> 00:05:55.719
but they're all
literally family-orientated.

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:59.195
But they have their beliefs
they don't want to give up.

00:05:59.255 --> 00:06:00.660
And that's Colorado.

00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:02.987
We're not trying to change your mind.

00:06:03.054 --> 00:06:04.954
We don't want you to go anywhere else.

00:06:05.021 --> 00:06:07.903
Come and enjoy
but don't bring your problems here.

00:06:08.548 --> 00:06:11.678
Coloradoans like people,
we just don't like their problems.

00:06:12.858 --> 00:06:14.526
-That's my look at it.
-Well said.

00:06:14.593 --> 00:06:16.064
-[laughter]
-That's great.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:17.710
Don't bring your problems.

00:06:17.777 --> 00:06:21.659
All right guys. Thank you.
I haven't gotten to town yet. Thank you.

00:06:25.868 --> 00:06:28.381
There you can see
the San Juans in the distance.

00:06:28.448 --> 00:06:31.001
Way out there. Snow-capped peaks.

00:06:32.424 --> 00:06:34.263
Some 14,000 footers.

00:06:35.109 --> 00:06:37.536
And we're not even in Cortez yet, guys.

00:06:38.223 --> 00:06:39.243
Just pulled off

00:06:40.229 --> 00:06:42.971
and they were out and about
and wanting to talk.

00:06:43.038 --> 00:06:44.970
So we got lucky.

00:06:45.623 --> 00:06:49.210
All right, so here's what it looks like
coming into Cortez.

00:06:49.277 --> 00:06:50.287
Your basic strip,

00:06:51.312 --> 00:06:53.765
auto dealerships, gas stations,

00:06:54.249 --> 00:06:55.915
repair places,

00:06:55.982 --> 00:06:57.575
classic Western town.

00:07:02.147 --> 00:07:04.187
Nice little downtown here in Cortez.

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:08.073
Roughly 8,500 people in this town.

00:07:08.448 --> 00:07:10.473
We're up above 6,000 feet.

00:07:10.853 --> 00:07:13.010
Just north of 6,000.

00:07:13.566 --> 00:07:15.684
Let's check it out. What's going on?

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:22.645
There we go. A mural on the wall.

00:07:23.311 --> 00:07:26.866
Captures the desert landscape
outside of town.

00:07:26.933 --> 00:07:30.441
The old Spanish Trail circa 1840.

00:07:34.517 --> 00:07:36.140
-Morning.
-Hi there. How are you?

00:07:36.207 --> 00:07:37.368
-Doing well.
-Good.

00:07:37.435 --> 00:07:38.754
This is a nice place.

00:07:38.821 --> 00:07:41.515
-This is a great coffee shop.
-Great coffee shop.

00:07:41.582 --> 00:07:44.230
-In my opinion it's the best in town.
-Okay.

00:07:44.297 --> 00:07:45.731
-How's Cortez?
-Great.

00:07:46.254 --> 00:07:47.901
It's a diamond in the rough.

00:07:49.091 --> 00:07:50.791
It's a small town that's growing

00:07:50.858 --> 00:07:54.218
but slowly enough that it can manage it.

00:07:54.638 --> 00:07:57.622
So it's not changing its identity in a way

00:07:57.689 --> 00:08:00.098
where you can't recognize it
after a few years.

00:08:00.165 --> 00:08:01.048
-Okay.

00:08:01.115 --> 00:08:03.427
A lot of homesteading families
still live here.

00:08:03.494 --> 00:08:05.729
They're still ranching, still farming.

00:08:06.222 --> 00:08:10.247
There are a lot of individual entrepreneurs

00:08:10.321 --> 00:08:13.643
who are doing niche like truck gardens

00:08:13.710 --> 00:08:16.762
or a craft, or an art, or working remotely.

00:08:16.829 --> 00:08:18.510
So it's got a real mix of people.

00:08:18.577 --> 00:08:22.149
-I just met a guy making planters.
-Yeah, there's all kinds of guys.

00:08:22.216 --> 00:08:23.677
So this is a part of Colorado

00:08:23.744 --> 00:08:26.899
that the everyday person
can afford to some degree?

00:08:27.379 --> 00:08:30.944
-To some degree.
-There are 25,000 people in the county.

00:08:31.498 --> 00:08:33.871
About 8,000 here in Cortez.

00:08:33.938 --> 00:08:37.147
So you go to Durango,
it's a whole different environment.

00:08:37.214 --> 00:08:38.840
It's a college town.

00:08:39.891 --> 00:08:42.776
And Durango is 25,000 people in itself.

00:08:42.843 --> 00:08:46.326
-I'm gonna Telluride.
-Yeah, that's a whole different world.

00:08:46.393 --> 00:08:49.694
You have these little worlds
but they're very unique.

00:08:49.761 --> 00:08:52.017
'Cause Telluride used to be a mining town

00:08:52.084 --> 00:08:54.784
but now it's kind of a ski-yuppie…

00:08:55.741 --> 00:08:56.696
sorta…

00:08:56.763 --> 00:08:58.626
-So totally different vibe up there?

00:08:58.693 --> 00:09:01.646
And one of the key
unique things about Cortez is

00:09:01.713 --> 00:09:03.926
it has a Ute reservation to the south

00:09:03.993 --> 00:09:06.815
and the Navajo reservation
to the west and the south.

00:09:06.882 --> 00:09:09.613
And that's all pretty much undeveloped land

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:11.488
so it's not gonna sprawl.

00:09:11.985 --> 00:09:15.488
-And you got stuff going on here.
-Oh, there's a lot going on.

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:18.682
Nice people. How you doing?

00:09:18.749 --> 00:09:19.778
[woman] Doing great.

00:09:19.859 --> 00:09:22.236
-I'm making a video of the area.
-Nice.

00:09:22.303 --> 00:09:25.670
Yeah what are you doing here?
Coffee, treats, you have art.

00:09:25.737 --> 00:09:27.520
We do. We have a gallery.

00:09:27.587 --> 00:09:29.958
This exhibition
typically changes every month.

00:09:30.025 --> 00:09:32.472
The next one will be
a birding festival theme.

00:09:32.539 --> 00:09:34.173
-Birding festival?
-Yeah.

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:36.117
How's it going? How do you like town?

00:09:36.184 --> 00:09:39.955
I like it. It's a lot of fun.
I like teaching about the area.

00:09:40.022 --> 00:09:41.326
-Did you grow up here?

00:09:41.393 --> 00:09:44.083
I came from the Navajo Nation in Arizona.

00:09:44.150 --> 00:09:45.033
You're Dine'?

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:47.420
Yeah. I'm half Navajo and half Irish.

00:09:47.487 --> 00:09:50.203
How's it living on the res and off the res?

00:09:50.270 --> 00:09:51.659
What is your experience?

00:09:51.726 --> 00:09:54.179
-Is it like two different worlds?
-Very different.

00:09:54.246 --> 00:09:56.866
I came from a small community
called Naslini.

00:09:56.933 --> 00:09:59.899
And grocery stores
are like 30 minutes to an hour away

00:09:59.966 --> 00:10:02.023
depending on where you want to go.

00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:04.811
My school was 30 minutes away
when I was in high school

00:10:04.878 --> 00:10:06.502
and growing up and everything.

00:10:06.583 --> 00:10:07.974
It's a different world.

00:10:08.541 --> 00:10:09.976
-How you doing, sir?
-How you doing?

00:10:10.043 --> 00:10:11.106
You live in Cortez?

00:10:11.173 --> 00:10:13.346
No. I live down in Towaoc down there.

00:10:13.413 --> 00:10:17.016
Big difference between
Ute and Dine' or not so much?

00:10:18.153 --> 00:10:20.588
Oh we have our differences.
I know that there's

00:10:20.655 --> 00:10:23.914
pretty much like what people say
is bad blood between us.

00:10:23.981 --> 00:10:26.563
But that's like back way back in the day.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:27.513
-Okay.

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.016
Yeah. I believe so.

00:10:29.083 --> 00:10:32.264
I would say there is some people
that still hold that prejudice.

00:10:32.331 --> 00:10:34.455
But there's a lot of people
like me and him

00:10:34.522 --> 00:10:37.493
that just don't care
about that beef and we get along.

00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:39.641
-The beef's way in the past, huh?
-Yes.

00:10:39.708 --> 00:10:42.734
-And you're Ute right?
-Yeah. I'm Ute and Navajo.

00:10:42.801 --> 00:10:45.103
Oh wow. So the battle's within.

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:48.260
Yeah. The cultural stuff is very similar.

00:10:48.727 --> 00:10:51.761
-Okay.
-It's almost identical, you know.

00:10:51.828 --> 00:10:54.776
And just the languages
are different you know.

00:10:55.153 --> 00:10:58.172
Because like they do
the Native American church

00:10:58.239 --> 00:11:02.666
through what I've seen is
several different Native American tribes,

00:11:02.733 --> 00:11:06.703
they almost spot on,
the same way how they pray.

00:11:07.113 --> 00:11:09.339
-They believe in a creator.
-Gotcha.

00:11:09.406 --> 00:11:10.864
Give thanks to that as well.

00:11:10.931 --> 00:11:14.348
But some of them like my dad,
he incorporates Jesus,

00:11:14.415 --> 00:11:18.303
and my mom incorporates Jesus
in their prayers as well, so…

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:19.253
-Interesting.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:22.249
They kind of just
add as they go you know, so…

00:11:22.316 --> 00:11:24.573
-Right on. See ya.
-See ya brother.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:27.124
-What do you want to show me?
-The hogan.

00:11:27.191 --> 00:11:28.521
The hogan. Oh cool.

00:11:29.188 --> 00:11:32.198
People still live in this today
in the Southwest.

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:35.083
-Still out on the rez right now?
-Yeah.

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:38.401
I know a lot of people,
even my cousins, that grew up like this.

00:11:38.468 --> 00:11:41.095
I have a hogan within my family.

00:11:41.775 --> 00:11:45.657
That one's used for ceremonial purposes
because we don't live here.

00:11:46.070 --> 00:11:48.703
But typically this is
a house you would live in.

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:50.883
It's encapsulated in red clay.

00:11:50.950 --> 00:11:54.627
Sometimes it doesn't have red clay
but it stays in an octagon shape.

00:11:55.083 --> 00:11:57.650
And the cool thing is
you always walk clockwise.

00:11:57.717 --> 00:12:01.087
Where the sun rises, that's where
you want your door to be showing.

00:12:01.154 --> 00:12:04.739
Okay. When you walk in here,
you would never walk that way?

00:12:04.806 --> 00:12:06.823
-You only walk this way?
-Yeah clockwise.

00:12:06.890 --> 00:12:10.840
'Cause when you let life into your house
you want to keep going where life goes.

00:12:10.907 --> 00:12:14.600
-So when you're living in here
at all times you go clockwise?

00:12:14.667 --> 00:12:16.926
Keep going around.
Even if you drop something.

00:12:16.993 --> 00:12:20.866
Like if I drop that I gotta go
all the way around if I'm not near it.

00:12:20.933 --> 00:12:22.345
That's just how it goes.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:25.062
-That is so cool.
-Yeah.

00:12:25.720 --> 00:12:28.692
So people who live in it.
It would have a dirt floor.

00:12:28.759 --> 00:12:30.034
It would be flat.

00:12:30.101 --> 00:12:32.371
-So it stays cool in the summers?
-Yeah.

00:12:32.438 --> 00:12:33.892
And warm during the winters.

00:12:33.959 --> 00:12:37.077
You typically wouldn't have
a giant hole like this.

00:12:37.144 --> 00:12:40.998
We just have that because we don't have
like a wood burning stove in here.

00:12:41.065 --> 00:12:44.857
But it would go all the way up
and you would cover the holes up there

00:12:44.924 --> 00:12:48.146
so that no precipitation
or climate gets in.

00:12:48.213 --> 00:12:49.096
-Okay.

00:12:49.163 --> 00:12:52.723
And when you cook on the wood burning
stove it heats up your house.

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.426
So you have family members
still living like this?

00:12:55.493 --> 00:12:58.193
They don't have a normal house.
They stay in the hogan.

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:02.366
Yeah. And I even have cousins where
they still don't have water or electricity.

00:13:02.433 --> 00:13:04.463
They have to haul water, haul coal.

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:07.994
Are they on social media, phones,
or are they removed from that too?

00:13:08.061 --> 00:13:10.056
No. They don't even speak English.

00:13:10.123 --> 00:13:12.484
-They speak fluent Navajo.
-No way.

00:13:12.551 --> 00:13:17.217
Do you notice a big difference between the
people that have stayed out of technology

00:13:17.284 --> 00:13:18.958
versus the ones that are in it?

00:13:19.025 --> 00:13:19.908
Yeah.

00:13:19.975 --> 00:13:22.753
I mean they're pretty much detached
as you would think.

00:13:22.820 --> 00:13:24.938
Like they don't know the political climate.

00:13:25.005 --> 00:13:27.855
They don't know anything
that's going on in the real world

00:13:27.922 --> 00:13:30.444
besides newspapers
and what people tell them.

00:13:30.983 --> 00:13:34.053
And they kind of stay
with the politics on the reservation

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:36.582
because that's
what's gonna affect them the most.

00:13:37.180 --> 00:13:41.053
Do you feel like you're sort of
in between two worlds?

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:44.199
Oh definitely.
Since I'm half Navajo and half Irish.

00:13:44.266 --> 00:13:46.345
I used to get made fun of for being White

00:13:46.412 --> 00:13:49.370
and then I get made fun of
for being Native.

00:13:49.836 --> 00:13:52.640
So I'm like constantly never fitting in.

00:13:52.707 --> 00:13:54.603
-Neither here nor there.
-No.

00:13:54.670 --> 00:13:56.426
But I grew up Navajo.

00:13:56.493 --> 00:13:58.396
I grew up on the rez my whole life.

00:13:58.463 --> 00:14:01.399
-You identify more with that than Irish?
-Oh definitely.

00:14:01.466 --> 00:14:03.476
I don't know much about Irish culture.

00:14:03.543 --> 00:14:06.679
For ceremonial purposes,
my siblings, they're preteens.

00:14:07.073 --> 00:14:09.226
They go through puberty ceremonies.

00:14:09.293 --> 00:14:12.209
So they last a couple of days.
Four days max.

00:14:12.603 --> 00:14:16.345
And my little sister should be
having a ceremony, one of those soon.

00:14:16.412 --> 00:14:19.987
-I think that rite of passage
or whatever you call it is so important.

00:14:20.054 --> 00:14:22.214
-We don't really have that.
-Yeah, no.

00:14:22.281 --> 00:14:25.099
It's just celebrating manhood,
celebrating womanhood.

00:14:25.166 --> 00:14:26.314
-So cool.
-Mm-hmm.

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:30.620
You've made 50 Native videos
in the last four years.

00:14:30.687 --> 00:14:33.005
[woman] Everything from
cowboys and Indians.

00:14:33.072 --> 00:14:34.333
You love it out here?

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:37.687
Oh yeah. I've been out here since '89.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:39.351
-Where are you from?

00:14:39.418 --> 00:14:40.301
England.

00:14:40.368 --> 00:14:42.393
-I was trying to pinpoint the accent.

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:45.351
-You sort of lost a lot of the English bit.
-Yeah.

00:14:45.418 --> 00:14:48.198
England is beautiful
but it's just flat and green.

00:14:48.932 --> 00:14:49.815
-Same, same.

00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:54.432
Here you drive two hours that way, and two
hours that way, it's a different reality.

00:14:54.499 --> 00:14:55.516
-Right yeah.

00:14:55.583 --> 00:14:58.742
Yeah, two hours to Arches,
two hours to Monument Valley.

00:14:58.809 --> 00:15:00.985
That's why I started doing the films.

00:15:01.370 --> 00:15:03.187
Cool, you're still selling them too.

00:15:03.254 --> 00:15:04.143
-Yeah
-DVD.

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:05.555
Not as much but…

00:15:07.982 --> 00:15:10.249
[news anchor]
…to the UN's top aid coordinator

00:15:10.316 --> 00:15:13.316
who briefed
the UN Security Council on Wednesday.

00:15:13.384 --> 00:15:16.269
[man] Let's go outside
so you can see from the outside.

00:15:16.336 --> 00:15:18.216
Then we'll come in through the door.

00:15:18.283 --> 00:15:19.948
-You're another British man?
-Yes.

00:15:20.015 --> 00:15:21.883
-I met David.
-Which David?

00:15:21.950 --> 00:15:24.326
I don't know he's got a British accent.

00:15:24.393 --> 00:15:26.793
-There's another one?
-What's going on in Cortez?

00:15:26.860 --> 00:15:29.372
-There's another one here?
-The Redcoats have come.

00:15:29.439 --> 00:15:31.341
I'll have to like find my competition.

00:15:31.408 --> 00:15:33.708
[woman] We have one
on the air too on Saturday.

00:15:33.775 --> 00:15:36.711
Oh and you have your studio in a safe.

00:15:36.778 --> 00:15:39.071
This is our story vault.

00:15:39.138 --> 00:15:41.865
So anybody from the community
can come and use this.

00:15:41.932 --> 00:15:43.843
We kept all the old bank stuff going.

00:15:43.910 --> 00:15:46.416
Okay so this is
the local radio station here?

00:15:46.483 --> 00:15:48.438
Yeah we're the community radio station.

00:15:48.505 --> 00:15:50.452
So we do local news.

00:15:50.519 --> 00:15:55.017
We also have all-volunteer DJs
who come in and do two-hour music shows.

00:15:55.084 --> 00:15:55.967
-Great.

00:15:56.034 --> 00:15:58.435
They're kind of
the masters of their own destiny.

00:15:58.502 --> 00:16:01.594
We don't tell them what to play.
It's all powered by them.

00:16:02.762 --> 00:16:06.141
-This is where you're running it from?
-Yeah this is our live studio.

00:16:06.208 --> 00:16:08.638
-Is this an NPR affiliate?
-Yep.

00:16:08.705 --> 00:16:10.470
How's public radio these days?

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:13.973
It has its ups and downs.
We are optimistic though.

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:16.788
This is so cool.
For a town of only 8,500 people

00:16:16.855 --> 00:16:21.258
I didn't think you'd have
such a well-organized setup like this.

00:16:21.850 --> 00:16:25.620
Yeah and you're here during our fund drive
too so it's like a very fun time.

00:16:25.687 --> 00:16:27.725
-Okay you want people to donate?
-Oh yes.

00:16:27.792 --> 00:16:29.482
Okay donate to what's the name?

00:16:29.549 --> 00:16:33.234
www.KSJD.org Hit the red donate button
and then we'll take it from there.

00:16:33.301 --> 00:16:36.920
-You're gonna show me the theater?
-Yeah, but let's go in the other door.

00:16:36.987 --> 00:16:38.278
-Okay gotcha.

00:16:38.345 --> 00:16:40.763
Okay so another British man in town.

00:16:40.830 --> 00:16:42.651
How'd you end up in Cortez?

00:16:42.718 --> 00:16:45.923
Well I used to come here
for mountain biking and now I live here.

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:47.379
-That's wild.
-There we go.

00:16:47.446 --> 00:16:49.505
-So this is our theater.
-Okay cool.

00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:54.562
Nice.
So you're putting on performances here?

00:16:54.629 --> 00:16:57.953
Yes we have perhaps
three or four a week at the moment.

00:16:58.020 --> 00:17:02.798
And we have everything from
live storytelling, to bands, movies, etc.

00:17:02.865 --> 00:17:05.115
Come and see
we have this wonderful projector.

00:17:05.182 --> 00:17:06.065
-Mm-hmm.

00:17:06.132 --> 00:17:09.074
So we can also stream from this as well.

00:17:09.141 --> 00:17:13.063
There's a little nugget of culture
in the desert I guess.

00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:15.530
-Totally different world here.
How do you like it?

00:17:15.597 --> 00:17:16.993
I love living here.

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:19.743
-You miss the UK or no?
-I go there quite a lot.

00:17:19.823 --> 00:17:21.476
-Okay.
-But this is my home.

00:17:21.543 --> 00:17:23.306
Why do you love it so much?

00:17:23.373 --> 00:17:27.863
It's the opposite of where I'm from.
I love the desert. It's so beautiful.

00:17:28.351 --> 00:17:31.859
Whereas I'm from Scotland,
so it's very green and rainy there.

00:17:31.926 --> 00:17:34.972
Here it's very red and dry
and I like the contrast.

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:38.793
-So people come in Cortez,
Sunflower Theatre…

00:17:38.860 --> 00:17:40.396
-KSJD is the radio station.

00:17:40.463 --> 00:17:41.814
You can also get us online.

00:17:41.881 --> 00:17:45.833
We have people who listen in Argentina,
the UK, Germany, Switzerland.

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:49.832
You just go to www.KSJD.org
and hit the play button. It's that easy.

00:17:49.899 --> 00:17:50.782
-Great.

00:17:56.288 --> 00:18:00.646
[Peter] Here we have a cinema, and guys,
we have a ton of ground to cover today.

00:18:00.713 --> 00:18:02.713
We're gonna go through these towns

00:18:03.401 --> 00:18:04.989
give you a flavor, a sample.

00:18:06.279 --> 00:18:08.275
People waving. Nice people here.

00:18:09.141 --> 00:18:11.269
But then I have to move on because

00:18:11.336 --> 00:18:13.924
we got to get up to Telluride
before sundown.

00:18:14.507 --> 00:18:15.390
Show you that.

00:18:15.862 --> 00:18:18.086
Cool place, Cortez. Nice people.

00:18:18.688 --> 00:18:21.570
I mean I've literally been here
an hour and a half

00:18:22.314 --> 00:18:26.203
and I've spent my whole time
talking to locals.

00:18:30.010 --> 00:18:33.212
You can see the La Plata Mountains
in the background.

00:18:33.279 --> 00:18:37.266
I believe part of the San Juans
which are part of the Rockies.

00:18:37.333 --> 00:18:39.523
Got a massive park here in Cortez.

00:18:39.996 --> 00:18:41.349
A ton of soccer fields.

00:18:42.050 --> 00:18:44.432
This is just a neighborhood
right near downtown.

00:18:44.499 --> 00:18:46.193
Well actually in downtown.

00:18:46.788 --> 00:18:48.593
These homes right here,

00:18:48.660 --> 00:18:50.587
I was looking on Zillow last night.

00:18:51.071 --> 00:18:53.602
Roughly around $350,000.

00:18:54.130 --> 00:18:56.049
Some a little less some a little more.

00:18:56.116 --> 00:18:59.363
But that seemed to be the average
around this neighborhood.

00:18:59.810 --> 00:19:04.619
The median income in Cortez
is roughly around $54,000.

00:19:04.686 --> 00:19:06.465
Family median income.

00:19:07.330 --> 00:19:09.593
Nationally we're around $84,000.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:11.826
So obviously it's lower here.

00:19:12.761 --> 00:19:15.187
But for the country, especially Colorado,

00:19:15.254 --> 00:19:18.468
I would think these are
some great housing prices.

00:19:18.535 --> 00:19:20.643
I mean
$350,000 isn't cheap but

00:19:20.710 --> 00:19:23.399
a lot of neighborhoods
that look like this around the country

00:19:23.466 --> 00:19:25.450
I'm seeing double that price easily,

00:19:25.518 --> 00:19:28.510
and California looking, well triple.

00:19:29.485 --> 00:19:31.842
So some cool homes.

00:19:31.909 --> 00:19:34.912
It was designed well here.
You can see a large median.

00:19:34.979 --> 00:19:36.405
Some nice old churches.

00:19:37.312 --> 00:19:38.783
And it's just got a nice

00:19:39.483 --> 00:19:43.243
calm pleasant interesting feel to it.

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:48.490
So as the British guys were saying
and the guys we met first this morning

00:19:48.936 --> 00:19:51.144
it's just this weird hybrid zone of

00:19:51.991 --> 00:19:55.507
desert going into mountains
not too far away,

00:19:56.109 --> 00:19:58.951
Natives, ranching culture.

00:19:59.626 --> 00:20:00.989
For a small town

00:20:01.056 --> 00:20:04.659
quite an interesting
cool mix going on here.

