Now back to the story.

00:21:46.478 --> 00:21:48.424
Wow, what a place.

00:21:49.384 --> 00:21:50.897
Almost at 9,000 ft.

00:21:51.892 --> 00:21:54.881
Rico means rich in Spanish.

00:21:55.655 --> 00:21:57.644
And so in 1879

00:21:58.282 --> 00:22:00.914
that's when the silver was struck.

00:22:02.147 --> 00:22:03.611
And this town grew to

00:22:04.592 --> 00:22:07.145
roughly 5,000 people back in the day.

00:22:09.892 --> 00:22:10.775
Now…

00:22:11.782 --> 00:22:12.665
Rico's quiet.

00:22:14.478 --> 00:22:16.075
Looks like everything's closed.

00:22:16.142 --> 00:22:17.965
We got a theater cafe.

00:22:18.614 --> 00:22:19.677
For sale.

00:22:21.032 --> 00:22:22.151
Beautiful building.

00:22:23.426 --> 00:22:25.434
Look at these old door handles.

00:22:28.502 --> 00:22:30.326
Looks like an old bar in there.

00:22:32.029 --> 00:22:32.912
Interesting.

00:22:33.895 --> 00:22:37.503
There's not one person here in Rico
at this point in time.

00:22:41.295 --> 00:22:42.943
Bike shop. Nice.

00:22:44.002 --> 00:22:45.494
And here's the museum.

00:22:47.361 --> 00:22:49.881
I don't think it's open. Nope.

00:22:52.402 --> 00:22:53.720
And a coffee shop.

00:22:55.482 --> 00:22:57.541
Oh that's a cool coffee shop. Okay.

00:22:58.069 --> 00:23:01.363
Maybe they just closed down everything
super early here.

00:23:02.352 --> 00:23:04.383
The median family income here

00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:07.148
is around $105,000.

00:23:07.215 --> 00:23:08.945
So above the national average.

00:23:09.556 --> 00:23:11.248
And I think that's just because

00:23:11.665 --> 00:23:13.616
people are going not far away

00:23:14.123 --> 00:23:17.762
over another pass to a thriving economy.

00:23:17.829 --> 00:23:19.064
That being Telluride.

00:23:23.023 --> 00:23:23.906
Hey buddy.

00:23:27.842 --> 00:23:30.529
-What's your dog's name?
-[man] That's Golda.

00:23:30.596 --> 00:23:33.315
[Peter] This has gotta be
a cool USPS to work at.

00:23:33.916 --> 00:23:35.302
It's pretty chill huh?

00:23:35.369 --> 00:23:39.512
[man] Yeah pretty laid back, relaxed.
The people here all super friendly.

00:23:39.579 --> 00:23:43.331
-So are most people here working
up in Telluride? Is that the story?

00:23:43.398 --> 00:23:44.607
Yeah.

00:23:44.674 --> 00:23:47.872
I would say probably
about half the town works in Telluride.

00:23:47.939 --> 00:23:50.535
The other half have some way
of working from home.

00:23:50.602 --> 00:23:53.204
-You got one of
the only jobs in town it looks like.

00:23:53.271 --> 00:23:56.440
Yeah. There's here,
the gas station, the enterprise,

00:23:56.825 --> 00:23:58.645
and the town office.

00:23:58.712 --> 00:24:02.415
Where you have the town clerk,
and the town manager, and the librarian.

00:24:02.482 --> 00:24:04.100
-Okay.
-That's about it.

00:24:04.167 --> 00:24:06.487
So it's a lot of this? Just silent road?

00:24:06.554 --> 00:24:07.810
-Yeah.
-No cars?

00:24:07.877 --> 00:24:10.186
When I first got here
I saw the left turn lane.

00:24:10.253 --> 00:24:15.025
I'm like why do they have the left turn
lane at this tiny little town?

00:24:15.092 --> 00:24:18.945
But I figured out why. If you're here
for a couple of winters. All right…

00:24:19.012 --> 00:24:22.035
They have to plow the snow somewhere.
We have street parking.

00:24:22.102 --> 00:24:24.182
They don't want to plow it into the cars.

00:24:24.249 --> 00:24:27.262
So they plow it into the center
where that left turn lane is.

00:24:27.329 --> 00:24:30.877
You're getting a ton of snow right?
We're almost at 9,000 feet.

00:24:30.944 --> 00:24:34.052
-Um 8,800. So yeah.
-Yeah.

00:24:34.119 --> 00:24:37.253
Two winters ago…
I live just not too far from here.

00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:41.743
And my dogs could just
walk up and over my five foot tall fence.

00:24:41.810 --> 00:24:44.062
-Where'd you move from?
-Originally Oklahoma.

00:24:44.616 --> 00:24:45.991
Okay. That's a contrast.

00:24:46.058 --> 00:24:48.286
My wife wanted to do
a traveling nurse thing.

00:24:48.353 --> 00:24:49.340
-Oh cool.

00:24:49.407 --> 00:24:52.415
So we moved into an RV
and traveled around for a while.

00:24:52.482 --> 00:24:55.271
Got to this area, decided we liked it, and…

00:24:55.338 --> 00:24:56.391
-That's awesome.

00:24:56.458 --> 00:25:00.712
Ended up taking this job and buying
the house from the previous postmaster.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:02.956
-Oh nice.
-She was retiring.

00:25:03.023 --> 00:25:03.939
Bought her house.

00:25:04.006 --> 00:25:05.553
-Change of the guard.
-Yeah.

00:25:05.620 --> 00:25:06.989
-What's your name?
-Michael.

00:25:07.056 --> 00:25:08.131
-Michael, Peter.

00:25:08.198 --> 00:25:09.332
-Thank you.
-Yeah.

00:25:09.399 --> 00:25:12.101
You're the only person I've seen in town.

00:25:12.168 --> 00:25:14.527
Well there will be people
at the gas station.

00:25:14.594 --> 00:25:17.682
There's people playing on the playground
behind the school.

00:25:17.749 --> 00:25:21.017
Actually one of the other drawbacks
is we no longer have a school.

00:25:21.084 --> 00:25:24.607
So if you have kids you have to take them
to Telluride or Dolores.

00:25:24.992 --> 00:25:26.474
-Take care.
-Nice to meet you.

00:25:26.541 --> 00:25:27.659
You too. Thank you.

00:25:33.209 --> 00:25:35.268
Just listen to this place you guys.

00:25:36.877 --> 00:25:37.995
There's tire noise.

00:25:39.345 --> 00:25:41.481
Something running over there but that's it.

00:25:41.548 --> 00:25:42.431
Little wind.

00:25:46.439 --> 00:25:47.677
Mine Shaft Inn.

00:25:48.439 --> 00:25:50.969
And arrows going over.

00:26:08.002 --> 00:26:10.775
-You live here but you work in Telluride?
-Yeah.

00:26:10.842 --> 00:26:13.731
This is not being rented out?
The mountain owns this.

00:26:13.798 --> 00:26:15.478
No this is owned by the mountain.

00:26:15.545 --> 00:26:18.655
They own one or two properties
down the road.

00:26:18.722 --> 00:26:22.651
And then if you work for the mountain
for the season you can get a room here.

00:26:22.724 --> 00:26:25.034
-Telluride ski resort.
Huge mountain resort.

00:26:25.101 --> 00:26:28.851
And so they're buying up real estate
in the surrounding towns for employees?

00:26:28.918 --> 00:26:30.349
-Is that what that is?
-Yeah.

00:26:30.416 --> 00:26:33.155
-Well it's good you got a place to live.
-It's not bad.

00:26:33.222 --> 00:26:35.010
You gonna come back next season?

00:26:35.077 --> 00:26:37.371
We'll see. See if I can get a real job.

00:26:39.818 --> 00:26:42.105
All right some more empty storefronts.

00:26:42.172 --> 00:26:43.335
It's pretty tough

00:26:44.102 --> 00:26:46.824
to make something fly
in these parts I believe.

00:26:46.891 --> 00:26:50.158
Beautiful, beautiful old buildings.

00:26:50.937 --> 00:26:53.290
Oh you can see the snow from the winter.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:56.343
How you doing sir?

00:26:56.410 --> 00:26:57.293
-Good.

00:26:57.360 --> 00:26:59.793
-They still have church service up there?
-No.

00:27:00.312 --> 00:27:01.318
Church is done.

00:27:01.385 --> 00:27:03.857
I'm making a video
on the whole part of the state.

00:27:03.924 --> 00:27:05.735
-Cortez to Telluride.
-Wow.

00:27:05.802 --> 00:27:08.240
So I wanted to put Rico in on it.

00:27:08.307 --> 00:27:10.218
-Are you from here?
-I live here, yes.

00:27:10.285 --> 00:27:13.066
-What's it like living here?
-You gotta want to do it.

00:27:13.133 --> 00:27:16.354
-You gotta be committed.
-It's pretty isolated and uh…

00:27:16.421 --> 00:27:19.192
This winter wasn't
but the winter's can be fairly harsh.

00:27:19.259 --> 00:27:20.792
I love the winters actually.

00:27:20.859 --> 00:27:23.820
It's interesting.
I've seen people come and think,

00:27:23.894 --> 00:27:26.023
"Oh wow, this is where I want to live."

00:27:26.505 --> 00:27:30.650
So they buy a property and everything
and then a year later they're gone.

00:27:30.717 --> 00:27:32.015
-The honeymoon wears off.
-Yeah.

00:27:32.082 --> 00:27:35.730
That doesn't bother me.
You know I'm retired. I don't have to do…

00:27:35.797 --> 00:27:38.197
-Okay you don't have to work
around here in town.

00:27:38.264 --> 00:27:41.357
Drive to Telluride to work
or Cortez or wherever.

00:27:41.424 --> 00:27:42.993
-You walking up this way?
-Yeah.

00:27:43.066 --> 00:27:44.495
-Can I go with you?
-Sure.

00:27:44.556 --> 00:27:46.416
-What's your name?
-Larry. What's yours?

00:27:46.483 --> 00:27:48.920
Peter. Nice to meet you.

00:27:48.987 --> 00:27:50.469
-What are you doing this for?

00:27:50.536 --> 00:27:53.044
Okay so I film, my wife edits,

00:27:53.622 --> 00:27:54.826
we go all over America.

00:27:54.893 --> 00:27:57.258
Every corner nook and cranny
you can think of.

00:27:57.325 --> 00:27:59.325
-Teach Americans about America.
-Great.

00:27:59.392 --> 00:28:02.091
We got a great country
with a lot of cool people,

00:28:02.541 --> 00:28:03.991
and we like to show it.

00:28:04.058 --> 00:28:04.941
Good for you.

00:28:05.008 --> 00:28:06.472
So that's what we do.

00:28:06.539 --> 00:28:08.991
Larry, do you know anything
about these buildings?

00:28:09.058 --> 00:28:11.639
-The courthouse?
-That's the courthouse. Okay.

00:28:12.062 --> 00:28:13.801
So they struck silver here.

00:28:14.252 --> 00:28:16.844
The place boomed to 5,000 people roughly.

00:28:17.298 --> 00:28:19.262
That was as large as it was gonna be.

00:28:19.842 --> 00:28:23.149
A few years later
the market on silver went south.

00:28:23.914 --> 00:28:25.662
The town did too. [chuckles]

00:28:26.412 --> 00:28:29.273
We're also home to silver
but a lot of gold and

00:28:29.856 --> 00:28:31.503
lead and everything else but

00:28:32.088 --> 00:28:33.195
also pyrites.

00:28:33.881 --> 00:28:37.783
It turns out the Atomic Energy Commission
was just getting going.

00:28:38.418 --> 00:28:41.372
And you need pyrites,
the sulfur from pyrites,

00:28:42.127 --> 00:28:43.445
to refine uranium.

00:28:43.852 --> 00:28:47.322
It was a real boom in the '50s.

00:28:47.782 --> 00:28:49.784
-Post atom bomb?
-Yeah, right.

00:28:49.851 --> 00:28:52.209
-Okay. So there was a boom afterwards.
-Yeah.

00:28:52.276 --> 00:28:55.528
And then it declined again.
And we're growing a little bit.

00:28:55.595 --> 00:28:58.031
We're about 270, 280.

00:28:58.098 --> 00:29:01.291
But half of that,
you know, we're standing here,

00:29:01.785 --> 00:29:03.941
that's a summer home. That's a summer home.

00:29:04.015 --> 00:29:06.751
Windham is a summer home.
That's a summer home.

00:29:06.818 --> 00:29:07.755
-Okay.

00:29:07.828 --> 00:29:09.361
-Half the population

00:29:10.202 --> 00:29:12.587
is really rich Texans

00:29:12.654 --> 00:29:15.384
and people from Arizona
who have second homes here.

00:29:15.767 --> 00:29:16.675
A lot of Texans?

00:29:17.162 --> 00:29:18.103
A lot of Texans.

00:29:18.522 --> 00:29:21.361
So what is a home like that
do you think roughly?

00:29:21.428 --> 00:29:23.195
Well it was affordable.

00:29:23.262 --> 00:29:26.455
The land and everything
you're probably looking about

00:29:26.522 --> 00:29:28.475
-$700,000.
-Okay.

00:29:29.628 --> 00:29:32.528
-But in Telluride that would be
like four times as much.

00:29:32.595 --> 00:29:34.841
-Five, six, seven times as much.
-Oh, wow!

00:29:34.908 --> 00:29:36.628
Yeah Telluride's crazy.

00:29:37.382 --> 00:29:39.395
It's a privilege to live on dirt roads.

00:29:39.462 --> 00:29:41.462
It's cool. I like this.

00:29:42.012 --> 00:29:45.145
People who bought this
really poured a lot of money into it.

00:29:45.212 --> 00:29:47.593
-It's beautiful.
-And then that's the Engle House.

00:29:47.660 --> 00:29:51.679
Charles Engle was one of
the real pioneers of the place.

00:29:52.262 --> 00:29:54.600
And then these are new builds up here.

00:29:54.667 --> 00:29:55.563
Okay.

00:29:55.630 --> 00:29:57.894
Is this a public street
or am I on a driveway?

00:29:57.961 --> 00:29:59.948
-You're on a public street.
-Okay.

00:30:00.015 --> 00:30:02.825
You don't want to
walk up someone's driveway.

00:30:02.892 --> 00:30:04.695
And you know, given Rico,

00:30:07.105 --> 00:30:09.408
go pretty much anywhere you want to go.

00:30:09.475 --> 00:30:11.048
People cool? Nice neighborhood?

00:30:11.115 --> 00:30:13.758
Yeah they don't mind you wandering around.

00:30:13.825 --> 00:30:15.525
-So this is your walk Larry?
-Yeah.

00:30:15.592 --> 00:30:16.755
Do your dirt road loop?

00:30:16.822 --> 00:30:19.351
Going to get the mail is a workout.
[laughs]

00:30:20.412 --> 00:30:24.269
This whole… just combed with roads.

00:30:24.862 --> 00:30:26.352
Because of the mines.

00:30:27.202 --> 00:30:28.496
There's something like

00:30:29.199 --> 00:30:30.892
70 mines

00:30:31.571 --> 00:30:33.248
within our eyes view.

00:30:33.315 --> 00:30:34.744
Oh really? Up in the hills?

00:30:34.811 --> 00:30:36.296
None of them are working now.

00:30:36.363 --> 00:30:38.529
-No more mining left in town at all?

00:30:38.596 --> 00:30:39.501
Not yet.

00:30:39.568 --> 00:30:41.002
We're sitting on

00:30:41.489 --> 00:30:45.158
one of the world's largest
molybdenum deposits.

00:30:45.762 --> 00:30:47.305
About 400 feet down.

00:30:47.372 --> 00:30:49.565
Molybdenum? I'm not even familiar with it.

00:30:49.632 --> 00:30:51.476
-Well it's a rare mineral.
-Okay.

00:30:51.543 --> 00:30:54.603
And it's used a lot
in electronics and things.

00:30:54.670 --> 00:30:58.716
The guy who owns a huge chunk
of the valley up here,

00:30:59.369 --> 00:31:01.998
has wanted to open
a molybdenum mine.

00:31:02.504 --> 00:31:05.378
And so far we've fought him off
from doing that.

00:31:05.445 --> 00:31:08.637
But if it became a national thing then

00:31:09.462 --> 00:31:10.764
it would probably happen.

00:31:10.831 --> 00:31:13.089
-This place is sitting
on a fortune basically?

00:31:13.156 --> 00:31:14.039
-Yeah.

00:31:14.545 --> 00:31:16.526
Well Larry, this is where we part ways.

00:31:16.593 --> 00:31:18.051
Good luck with your project.

00:31:18.118 --> 00:31:20.738
Thank you. I appreciate it.
Thanks for the knowledge.

00:31:20.805 --> 00:31:22.087
Thanks for the knowledge.

00:31:22.154 --> 00:31:23.787
-Take care.
-Take care. See ya.

00:31:26.264 --> 00:31:27.495
[water rushing]

00:31:30.962 --> 00:31:33.406
-[Peter] You got a sweet place, man.
-Thank you.

00:31:33.473 --> 00:31:35.335
-You digging it?
-Yeah I love it.

00:31:35.402 --> 00:31:36.931
We've been here since '21.

00:31:37.702 --> 00:31:40.550
And we lived over in Telluride since '09.

00:31:41.197 --> 00:31:43.138
It's quiet. There's parking.

00:31:43.205 --> 00:31:48.306
It's unfortunate that it's turned into
a second home community

00:31:48.373 --> 00:31:51.843
and half of the houses
are empty most of the year.

00:31:51.910 --> 00:31:52.793
-Gotcha.

00:31:52.860 --> 00:31:55.835
-Meanwhile the service community
can't find housing

00:31:55.902 --> 00:31:57.955
or can't live over there anymore.

00:31:58.022 --> 00:32:00.395
If you want to just jump over
or pull that off.

00:32:00.462 --> 00:32:01.877
I'll pull these guys inside.

00:32:01.944 --> 00:32:04.175
This is the newest building
on the property.

00:32:04.920 --> 00:32:08.731
Previous owners had
an infinite swim spa in it.

00:32:09.377 --> 00:32:10.548
Brick house here.

00:32:10.615 --> 00:32:13.617
I met a lady that told me she grew up

00:32:13.684 --> 00:32:17.798
with 16 siblings,
moms and dads, and extended family,

00:32:17.866 --> 00:32:20.447
in that house in the sixties or seventies.

00:32:20.514 --> 00:32:22.684
And that was when the mine was active here.

00:32:22.751 --> 00:32:23.950
Where were they from?

00:32:24.017 --> 00:32:26.985
Uh I think they live south
probably in Cortez now.

00:32:27.052 --> 00:32:29.585
Ute Native American, Ute tribe.

00:32:29.652 --> 00:32:30.994
Okay, I was there today.

00:32:31.061 --> 00:32:34.111
16 people. When there was 5,000 people
that lived in this town

00:32:34.178 --> 00:32:35.745
and now there's less than 300.

00:32:36.202 --> 00:32:39.095
What's awesome about this town
other than peace quiet nice architecture?

00:32:39.162 --> 00:32:41.438
That you and I get to meet
and just talk here.

00:32:42.212 --> 00:32:45.551
I think the dirt road
has something to do with that. Seriously.

00:32:45.618 --> 00:32:47.329
-It slows things down.
-I hate the dirt road.

00:32:47.410 --> 00:32:48.824
-You hate it?
-It's the dust.

00:32:48.891 --> 00:32:52.405
No I love it here. We have a good community
that are all working people

00:32:52.472 --> 00:32:55.408
that are happy to stop
and talk and hang out.

00:32:56.334 --> 00:32:58.216
-It's awesome.
-There's less ego.

00:32:59.242 --> 00:33:01.196
You're not flexing what you got here.

00:33:01.263 --> 00:33:02.146
No.

00:33:02.213 --> 00:33:03.604
It's not Aspen.

00:33:03.671 --> 00:33:05.024
Look I got wood all over.

00:33:05.091 --> 00:33:09.032
-I got my ladder just hanging out.
-But this place looks so awesome.

00:33:10.087 --> 00:33:12.441
-Yeah but this is a sweet town.
-I love it here.

00:33:12.508 --> 00:33:15.041
I mean you can't recreate stuff like this.

00:33:15.121 --> 00:33:17.453
No this house was built in 1888

00:33:17.892 --> 00:33:21.414
and I'm just feeling fortunate
that it's in my care

00:33:21.481 --> 00:33:24.254
and I don't want to ruin it.
It's been here a long time.

00:33:24.321 --> 00:33:26.670
-Do you have a family?
-I have a wife.

00:33:26.737 --> 00:33:29.187
And a dog. This is a foster.
You want a dog?

00:33:29.254 --> 00:33:31.317
I'm good right now. He's awesome.

00:33:31.384 --> 00:33:33.714
He is awesome.
A lot of young people here?

00:33:33.781 --> 00:33:38.485
Yeah a lot of people have gotten displaced
from Telluride as they lost housing

00:33:39.272 --> 00:33:43.039
and moved to Norwood,
Ridgeway, Down Valley,

00:33:43.757 --> 00:33:44.699
Montrose.

00:33:44.766 --> 00:33:47.106
And the ones that could afford to buy

00:33:47.532 --> 00:33:52.094
have established businesses
and careers over there or elsewhere

00:33:52.662 --> 00:33:55.035
have moved here
and it keeps growing every year.

00:33:55.102 --> 00:33:58.665
We have a new family,
young people, move in like us.

00:33:59.611 --> 00:34:02.247
Can… the buy-in is still expensive though.

00:34:02.314 --> 00:34:04.417
It's expensive but it's doable.

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:08.371
Okay. It's not Cortez prices.
It's not Telluride prices.

00:34:08.438 --> 00:34:09.461
It's in between.

00:34:09.528 --> 00:34:12.995
This house in Telluride
would be $13, $15 million.

00:34:13.062 --> 00:34:15.345
-Come on.
-Yeah. This property this house.

00:34:15.412 --> 00:34:17.201
-$15 mil?
-Easy.

00:34:17.268 --> 00:34:19.366
And then they lift the house, gut it,

00:34:19.719 --> 00:34:21.200
and totally remodel it.

00:34:21.774 --> 00:34:22.767
-The whole thing.
-Okay.

00:34:22.834 --> 00:34:25.208
Here I don't need to ask
what you spent but…

00:34:25.275 --> 00:34:29.243
This, my neighbors two houses,
up I think they spent 600,

00:34:29.812 --> 00:34:32.637
and it's a pretty large house
with a big property too.

00:34:32.704 --> 00:34:34.175
Okay. How many years ago?

00:34:34.827 --> 00:34:35.710
One.

00:34:35.777 --> 00:34:38.877
-Is it going up or did it chill out?
-It's kind of chilled out.

00:34:38.944 --> 00:34:40.815
There's not as much on the market.

00:34:44.722 --> 00:34:47.322
[Peter] You might have
the nicest trailer in America.

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:49.895
You should see the inside.
It's so awesome.

00:34:49.962 --> 00:34:52.175
-You want to show me?
-A little time capsule.

00:34:52.242 --> 00:34:53.283
I'll check it out.

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:55.825
-If you're cool, I'm making a video.
-That's fine.

00:34:56.345 --> 00:34:59.212
1974, '73.

00:35:02.737 --> 00:35:05.997
It's long. Yeah that's how they are.
This is the kid's room.

00:35:06.064 --> 00:35:07.829
-How many kids do you have?
-Two.

00:35:09.361 --> 00:35:10.700
You play electric guitar?

00:35:11.167 --> 00:35:12.305
-My husband does.

00:35:13.171 --> 00:35:15.041
-This is awesome.
-Isn't this is cool?

00:35:15.108 --> 00:35:16.049
This is so cool.

00:35:16.116 --> 00:35:19.405
This is what people
really freak out over is the… Alexa pause.

00:35:20.064 --> 00:35:24.867
Is the original avocado green appliances.

00:35:24.934 --> 00:35:27.317
-This is like from
the mid-century modern days.

00:35:27.384 --> 00:35:28.443
Look at your view.

00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:29.893
-Yeah.

00:35:30.564 --> 00:35:31.447
It's nice.

00:35:31.514 --> 00:35:33.417
-You're winning here. I love the sink.

00:35:33.484 --> 00:35:35.602
-I know. It's all original.

00:35:35.669 --> 00:35:38.667
-And you know the old wood paneling works.

00:35:38.734 --> 00:35:39.617
-Yeah.

00:35:39.684 --> 00:35:41.467
Sometimes it doesn't but this does.

00:35:41.534 --> 00:35:45.834
It does because it's so bright. Look at all
these windows right across from each other.

00:35:45.901 --> 00:35:46.933
-This is awesome.

00:35:47.014 --> 00:35:48.786
-We put in a nice stove.

00:35:48.853 --> 00:35:50.117
-Super efficient I bet.

00:35:50.184 --> 00:35:51.516
-So mostly heats.

00:35:52.202 --> 00:35:55.657
Heats with this but heat
just doesn't make it all the way down.

00:35:55.724 --> 00:35:57.348
-Okay that's where you guys are.

00:35:57.415 --> 00:35:58.387
-This way. Yeah.

00:35:58.454 --> 00:35:59.851
Here's the bathroom.

00:36:00.750 --> 00:36:02.377
Original tub.

00:36:05.101 --> 00:36:06.616
-And there you go.
-The master.

00:36:06.683 --> 00:36:08.656
-Keeping it simple.
-Keeping it simple.

00:36:08.723 --> 00:36:11.282
Compact living. Less than a thousand feet.

00:36:11.349 --> 00:36:14.616
Less than a thousand feet.
And then you built this roof overhead.

00:36:14.683 --> 00:36:16.047
-This was here.
-Okay.

00:36:16.114 --> 00:36:19.114
But yeah,
you have to do this in the mountains.

00:36:19.130 --> 00:36:20.989
-You happy you moved here?
-Yeah.

00:36:21.056 --> 00:36:23.049
-Did you come from Telluride?
-Yeah.

00:36:23.565 --> 00:36:24.916
That's a story in town huh?

00:36:24.983 --> 00:36:27.764
I still have a really strong
Telluride connection so.

00:36:27.831 --> 00:36:29.907
I just talked to a guy up here. Great guy.

00:36:29.974 --> 00:36:31.995
He moved a few years ago from Telluride.

00:36:32.062 --> 00:36:33.312
-Did he?
-Yep.

00:36:33.379 --> 00:36:36.141
-Who?
-He sort of looks like me, bald head.

00:36:36.208 --> 00:36:38.288
Actually I thought you might be that guy.

00:36:38.355 --> 00:36:40.643
-Yeah. He was my doppelganger.

00:36:46.685 --> 00:36:48.803
Let's see if the Enterprise is open.

00:36:50.601 --> 00:36:51.484
Nope.

00:36:52.116 --> 00:36:52.999
It's not.

00:36:54.091 --> 00:36:56.155
"Since 1892."

00:36:57.165 --> 00:36:59.614
And then we have the liquor store.

00:37:02.285 --> 00:37:04.728
What are they doing? Closing down?

00:37:04.795 --> 00:37:06.266
Some stuff in the fridge.

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:11.140
Looks like they've closed down.

00:37:11.715 --> 00:37:13.142
This town is cool you guys.

00:37:13.209 --> 00:37:15.747
This is really a unique

00:37:16.527 --> 00:37:18.187
special feel.

00:37:18.775 --> 00:37:20.866
All right. Let's get to Telluride.

00:37:20.933 --> 00:37:21.816
Final stop.

00:37:21.883 --> 00:37:23.335
[Western music]

00:37:44.635 --> 00:37:47.528
This is such a beautiful place.

00:37:47.595 --> 00:37:50.820
Telluride founded in 1878.

00:37:50.887 --> 00:37:52.627
Almost at 9,000 feet.

00:37:52.694 --> 00:37:55.857
I think it's like 8,700 something.

00:37:56.345 --> 00:37:58.824
And just a nice quaint downtown.

00:37:58.891 --> 00:38:00.739
Like they said back in Rico,

00:38:00.806 --> 00:38:03.828
everything is extremely expensive here.

00:38:04.941 --> 00:38:07.741
Season just ended for the year
last weekend.

00:38:08.214 --> 00:38:09.607
There are no ski tourists.

00:38:10.125 --> 00:38:11.931
Looks pretty quiet right now.

00:38:17.323 --> 00:38:19.003
Let's check out this bar.

00:38:20.333 --> 00:38:21.744
[patrons chattering]

00:38:23.765 --> 00:38:25.373
[Peter] Sheep pasture out there?

00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:27.840
-That was sheep pasture.
-So you guys are locals?

00:38:27.907 --> 00:38:29.136
Yes. Total locals.

00:38:29.203 --> 00:38:31.774
-Born and raised?
-Born and raised.

00:38:31.841 --> 00:38:34.533
-Hey Travis. Nice to see you.
-Good to see you.

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:36.656
How come you're not in some exotic place?

00:38:36.723 --> 00:38:38.196
-We have a baby.
-What?!

00:38:38.263 --> 00:38:39.391
Congratulations.

00:38:39.458 --> 00:38:41.291
-Oh that's awesome.
-Oh my gosh.

00:38:41.364 --> 00:38:43.373
-A baby what?
-Boy, Mason.

00:38:43.440 --> 00:38:45.129
Oh my gosh. Congratulations.

00:38:45.205 --> 00:38:47.000
-Yes. Thank you.
-Enjoy.

00:38:47.067 --> 00:38:49.047
We will. Yeah I gotta get home.

00:38:49.114 --> 00:38:49.997
Yeah you do.

00:38:50.064 --> 00:38:53.494
-[Peter] Not to the bar, to home right?
-Yeah not to the bar.

00:38:53.922 --> 00:38:56.002
-Big trouble.
-Gotta slide right by.

00:38:56.861 --> 00:38:58.789
[Peter] See you're from here?

00:38:58.856 --> 00:39:00.947
-Yes.
-Yeah we both grew up here.

00:39:01.014 --> 00:39:02.490
Fourth generation both sides.

00:39:02.556 --> 00:39:03.537
-Fourth gen?
-Yep.

00:39:03.604 --> 00:39:05.148
On both our mom's side.

00:39:05.215 --> 00:39:07.481
-Married? Couple?
-Happily.

00:39:07.548 --> 00:39:10.166
30 blissful years.

00:39:10.660 --> 00:39:12.218
Okay. Okay, cool.

00:39:12.285 --> 00:39:15.704
You were saying in there,
town is sort of dead right now right?

00:39:15.771 --> 00:39:16.889
This is off season.

00:39:17.363 --> 00:39:18.735
Skiing just closed.

00:39:19.482 --> 00:39:24.062
Now it's kind of construction season
until Memorial weekend

00:39:24.129 --> 00:39:26.314
when Mountain Film comes in.

00:39:26.381 --> 00:39:29.787
And then that starts the festival season.

00:39:29.854 --> 00:39:33.383
And it's busy all the way
until October really.

00:39:33.450 --> 00:39:36.245
And this is off season
because most of the people

00:39:36.312 --> 00:39:40.785
who work for the ski resort or restaurants,
and they are just dead tired.

00:39:40.852 --> 00:39:42.777
So they go for two weeks at a minimum.

00:39:42.844 --> 00:39:44.234
-They get out of town?

00:39:44.301 --> 00:39:47.666
Because the school's shut
for two weeks for spring break.

00:39:47.733 --> 00:39:51.398
-Do they plan the school being shut
right after the ski hills shuts?

00:39:51.465 --> 00:39:52.864
-Yes absolutely.
-No way.

00:39:52.931 --> 00:39:54.896
Because back in the day a long time ago

00:39:54.963 --> 00:39:58.220
they had like normal traditional
spring breaks and stuff.

00:39:58.287 --> 00:40:01.217
And everybody would leave
after the mountain closed anyway.

00:40:01.284 --> 00:40:04.449
So they're like we should change that.

00:40:04.923 --> 00:40:07.137
-Okay.
-And then they do two weeks.

00:40:07.204 --> 00:40:09.866
And a lot of people
still take three weeks anyways.

00:40:09.933 --> 00:40:12.158
-So this is as quiet as it gets basically.

00:40:12.225 --> 00:40:13.508
Yes, this is it.

00:40:13.905 --> 00:40:17.868
It was mining that kicked this place off
right? Back in the day, just like Rico?

00:40:17.935 --> 00:40:20.846
-Yeah the mining was really declining.

00:40:20.913 --> 00:40:24.707
And there was a bunch of locals
that were trying to find.

00:40:24.774 --> 00:40:27.785
the next industry to come in
and keep the town going.

00:40:27.852 --> 00:40:28.735
-Okay.

00:40:28.802 --> 00:40:32.580
And there was an investor
out of Aspen in Beverly Hills

00:40:32.647 --> 00:40:36.068
that came in and worked with
a bunch of the local miners

00:40:36.135 --> 00:40:39.581
to buy out a bunch of the ranches up on

00:40:40.062 --> 00:40:41.478
what is now Mountain Village.

00:40:41.545 --> 00:40:44.290
So there was actually ranching here also?

00:40:44.357 --> 00:40:47.105
Significant amount of ranching.
That's where my family,

00:40:47.172 --> 00:40:49.165
the miners were trying to move out.

00:40:49.669 --> 00:40:52.991
And my family are sheep herders
and we needed high country pasture.

00:40:53.058 --> 00:40:54.677
So in 1926

00:40:54.751 --> 00:40:57.472
which is Aldasoro's 100th year,

00:40:57.539 --> 00:41:00.115
my grandfather started buying property.

00:41:00.182 --> 00:41:02.064
He bought up about 11 homesteads

00:41:02.663 --> 00:41:06.282
throughout on Deep Creek Mesa and that's
where we would summer our sheep.

00:41:06.349 --> 00:41:08.159
-What was it called? I'm sorry?

00:41:08.226 --> 00:41:09.298
The Aldasoro Ranch.

00:41:09.365 --> 00:41:12.340
-Okay. Aldasoro Ranch.
So that's a development or something?

00:41:12.407 --> 00:41:15.138
Now a portion of our ranch
is still in agriculture

00:41:15.205 --> 00:41:17.105
and a portion of it has been developed.

00:41:17.172 --> 00:41:18.055
Okay cool.

00:41:18.122 --> 00:41:21.521
So yeah it was fortunate for us,
unfortunate for the miners,

00:41:21.588 --> 00:41:24.108
but it allowed them to move on.

00:41:24.175 --> 00:41:25.788
Which was ideal for them.

00:41:26.315 --> 00:41:29.451
This house right here
is where my mother grew up.

00:41:29.518 --> 00:41:30.401
-No way.

00:41:30.468 --> 00:41:33.888
-This is 123 South Oak
which is now a restaurant.

00:41:33.955 --> 00:41:36.453
Uno Dos Tres.
This is where we spent summers.

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:39.887
I was only here in the summertime
whereas Scott was here year round.

00:41:39.954 --> 00:41:43.331
-Where would you stay? Upstairs?
-Upstairs. The house is very small.

00:41:43.398 --> 00:41:47.553
And actually the windows because of the
Harchitectural Review Committee, HARC,

00:41:48.257 --> 00:41:50.934
you have to keep the same windows
and the same shapes.

00:41:51.001 --> 00:41:53.548
So those are the same ones
that have always been there.

00:41:54.026 --> 00:41:56.765
-So back in those days, rough and tumble,

00:41:57.501 --> 00:41:59.429
scrappy type of place right?

00:41:59.496 --> 00:42:02.755
Yeah. My grandfather worked at the mine.
He was the assayer.

00:42:03.160 --> 00:42:07.583
Whereas his grandfather
was the mill superintendent.

00:42:07.650 --> 00:42:10.428
-I found the right people.
You guys are super deep here.

00:42:10.495 --> 00:42:12.683
Super deep in sheep sh*t and mining.

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:16.483
She was just talking about
the Aldasoro side.

00:42:16.943 --> 00:42:18.703
This is the Anderson side.

00:42:18.770 --> 00:42:20.335
So her mother's side is…

00:42:20.788 --> 00:42:24.676
That's where she's fourth generation.
Her dad's side, only third.

00:42:25.085 --> 00:42:28.262
-Oh you're not a local then.
-No, no. It's like aw…

00:42:28.329 --> 00:42:31.934
How many third or fourth gens
are there? Like a handful probably.

00:42:32.001 --> 00:42:33.183
There's a good handful.

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:35.777
I'd say mostly some of
his cousins are probably…

00:42:35.844 --> 00:42:37.836
Schuler's and then the Ranta's

00:42:37.903 --> 00:42:41.583
and Mahoney's and Stephen's.

00:42:41.650 --> 00:42:44.538
-They stayed in the area.
-Yeah there's not a ton.

00:42:44.605 --> 00:42:48.186
Historic buildings
had to stay intact largely.

00:42:48.253 --> 00:42:51.817
-Which is great. You don't have to
mourn the loss of a bunch of history.

00:42:51.884 --> 00:42:56.249
[Peter] So big money comes in and says
I want to buy this for what, $5 million.

00:42:56.316 --> 00:42:57.726
-Yeah.
-Is that a fair guess?

00:42:57.793 --> 00:43:00.893
And says I want to change it up,
and nope they're not going to.

00:43:00.959 --> 00:43:02.318
You can have some changes.

00:43:02.385 --> 00:43:05.867
Yeah you can do some changes
but integrity of the structure

00:43:05.934 --> 00:43:07.197
needs to remain the same.

00:43:07.264 --> 00:43:09.179
-So for instance this house right here

00:43:09.246 --> 00:43:13.097
is where my great aunt,
my mom's aunt lived, Minnie Ackerman.

00:43:13.164 --> 00:43:14.534
She was a postmaster here.

00:43:14.601 --> 00:43:15.676
And see how the front

00:43:15.743 --> 00:43:20.415
you can see the wood is
a little bit older compared to the back?

00:43:20.482 --> 00:43:22.364
That whole thing was in the back

00:43:22.885 --> 00:43:25.814
and it was a shed
that they couldn't tear down.

00:43:25.881 --> 00:43:27.759
So that people that bought it…

00:43:27.826 --> 00:43:30.310
But there was a house up front
that was newer

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:34.793
that that was out of
the Period of Significance.

00:43:35.173 --> 00:43:38.000
Which is up to 1913.

00:43:38.532 --> 00:43:41.521
And so anything up to 1913

00:43:41.588 --> 00:43:44.926
had to stay intact as much as possible.

00:43:44.993 --> 00:43:47.793
So the house was torn down
but the shed in the back

00:43:47.860 --> 00:43:50.516
which is probably either a carriage shed

00:43:50.583 --> 00:43:54.238
or a garage or a coal shed
couldn't be torn down

00:43:54.305 --> 00:43:57.619
and that's what they brought up front
and made this into a bedroom.

00:43:57.686 --> 00:44:00.813
That one which was remodeled
and added on to,

00:44:01.244 --> 00:44:04.433
I think the last time that sold
was like $16 million.

00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:06.748
-This is $16 mi?
-Yeah.

00:44:06.815 --> 00:44:10.553
So this was where my great-grandmother
lived and then her son…

00:44:10.958 --> 00:44:12.004
But it's four lots.

00:44:12.071 --> 00:44:14.636
Cherry bought this
when it was a long time ago.

00:44:14.703 --> 00:44:15.873
It wasn't quite like this.

00:44:15.940 --> 00:44:17.848
It a different kind of beauty.

00:44:17.915 --> 00:44:21.215
-So you're saying this is four lots?
This is what we're looking at?

00:44:21.282 --> 00:44:24.462
-Yeah because town lots are 25 feet wide.

00:44:24.529 --> 00:44:25.412
-Okay.

00:44:25.479 --> 00:44:27.876
-117 or 125 deep.

00:44:27.943 --> 00:44:29.363
-Okay.
-Yeah.

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:31.652
You're right next to
the gondola and chair eight.

00:44:31.719 --> 00:44:32.767
Oh yeah.

00:44:32.835 --> 00:44:35.478
If you're a skier
you just walk right there.

00:44:35.545 --> 00:44:37.011
-And this used to be Larson's

00:44:37.078 --> 00:44:40.825
and there was like a horse pasture
right down here.

00:44:40.892 --> 00:44:42.204
-Horse pasture right here?

00:44:42.271 --> 00:44:43.284
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

00:44:43.351 --> 00:44:46.601
And now this is the gondola goes up.
Now you've got Coffee Cowboy.

00:44:46.668 --> 00:44:48.909
Okay there you go. Is that good coffee?

00:44:48.976 --> 00:44:50.894
-It's the best in town.
-It's great.

00:44:50.961 --> 00:44:53.604
What's a cup of Joe
here at the base of the mountain?

00:44:53.671 --> 00:44:55.170
-Eight bucks?
-Four bucks.

00:44:55.237 --> 00:44:56.528
-Oh that's not bad.
-Yeah.

00:44:56.595 --> 00:44:59.195
I'm actually surprised.
That's quite reasonable.

00:44:59.678 --> 00:45:02.442
For being here?
Isn't that like Starbucks prices?

00:45:02.928 --> 00:45:05.249
-No it's less than Starbucks.
-It's less.

00:45:05.316 --> 00:45:06.748
But it's better coffee.

00:45:06.815 --> 00:45:08.832
And it comes with fun attitude at times.

00:45:08.899 --> 00:45:10.881
-Are these your friends?
-Great friends.

00:45:10.948 --> 00:45:13.831
This is a small town.
We're friends with everybody.

00:45:13.898 --> 00:45:14.813
-You know everyone.

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:17.069
Well and we all got to pull together.

00:45:17.136 --> 00:45:19.338
-Haley plays hockey with us.

00:45:19.405 --> 00:45:22.412
I did a whitewater rescue class with Scott.

00:45:23.149 --> 00:45:26.168
-[Peter] So is there a good community here?
-Great community.

00:45:26.235 --> 00:45:28.964
That's one of the things
that really does keep us here.

00:45:29.031 --> 00:45:31.955
Seriously? I would have thought
a lot of people would have…

00:45:32.022 --> 00:45:34.243
I met some guys in Rico that left.

00:45:34.310 --> 00:45:35.733
-There's some of that right?

00:45:35.800 --> 00:45:37.453
There is some attrition.

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:41.722
But I think what you have to keep in mind
is that we were a small community before

00:45:41.789 --> 00:45:45.046
and we needed to
count on each other for different times.

00:45:45.113 --> 00:45:49.751
And that's why you won't ever hear us
saying anything derogatory about…

00:45:49.818 --> 00:45:51.481
-Or at least not too bad.

00:45:51.548 --> 00:45:55.582
Well we don't say anything that is negative
about tourism or the development

00:45:55.649 --> 00:45:59.980
because it's those phases that you
have to accept if you really love the area.

00:46:00.488 --> 00:46:04.664
And we do love it here and what
we've realized is over the last 30 years

00:46:05.415 --> 00:46:08.713
being a part of a community
has really charmed our life in that

00:46:08.780 --> 00:46:12.697
volunteer fire department,
all the kids organizations,

00:46:12.764 --> 00:46:15.158
skate club, soccer club, angel baskets.

00:46:15.225 --> 00:46:17.457
-So that's happening here.
-That's happening.

00:46:17.524 --> 00:46:20.105
And Scott you were saying
you were the fire chief?

00:46:20.172 --> 00:46:22.448
Volunteer fire chief for about five years.

00:46:22.515 --> 00:46:24.599
-Now I'm on search and rescue.

00:46:24.666 --> 00:46:27.771
And we're a small community.
So we do bluegrass.

00:46:27.838 --> 00:46:31.438
We do blues and brews.
We do mountain film. We do film fest.

00:46:31.505 --> 00:46:34.756
Kind of whatever we need
and the social part is fantastic.

00:46:34.823 --> 00:46:39.443
My dad was the mayor in the early '70s
when the ski area started.

00:46:39.510 --> 00:46:43.196
You know at that time there was
a bunch of hippies that moved to town.

00:46:43.263 --> 00:46:47.082
And there was kind of a ruckus
between the hippies and the miners.

00:46:47.149 --> 00:46:49.790
And really the hippies were more

00:46:50.179 --> 00:46:52.883
politically engaged.

00:46:53.964 --> 00:46:58.318
So you know there was a bunch of them
that got on town boards.

00:46:58.385 --> 00:47:00.366
Which overall it was great things.

00:47:00.433 --> 00:47:02.158
But there was some conflicts.

00:47:02.225 --> 00:47:06.043
And you know really some of the hippies
were pretty well-educated too.

00:47:06.110 --> 00:47:06.888
-Yeah.

00:47:06.955 --> 00:47:09.186
-And they left situations that

00:47:09.663 --> 00:47:12.967
were a lot more possibly progressive
than we were here.

00:47:13.401 --> 00:47:17.133
-And so that's how it is in a lot of
these towns across the country.

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:18.777
When the mining goes out

00:47:19.223 --> 00:47:20.556
and if they're beautiful

00:47:21.123 --> 00:47:23.464
the artists come in when it gets cheap.

00:47:23.531 --> 00:47:25.202
-Right.
-And that's what happened?

00:47:25.269 --> 00:47:27.098
This was one of my grandma's houses.

00:47:27.165 --> 00:47:28.048
-Oh nice.

00:47:28.645 --> 00:47:30.813
This is an example of full remodel.

00:47:30.880 --> 00:47:32.622
So that original house,

00:47:33.482 --> 00:47:34.365
stayed.

00:47:34.432 --> 00:47:35.738
Same with the shed.

00:47:35.805 --> 00:47:39.426
And then all this new section was added on.

00:47:39.493 --> 00:47:41.383
Are these mostly second homes?

00:47:41.450 --> 00:47:42.679
Or are they local homes?

00:47:42.746 --> 00:47:44.645
A lot of them these days are second.

00:47:44.725 --> 00:47:49.671
But you know, our second homeowners
or part-time homeowners

00:47:49.738 --> 00:47:52.038
contribute so much to our community.

00:47:52.105 --> 00:47:52.988
-They do.

00:47:53.055 --> 00:47:55.706
For all the 501c3s, the arts.

00:47:55.773 --> 00:47:58.044
-Property tax bill must be huge here.

00:47:58.111 --> 00:48:00.973
It can be significant, 
and in addition, what they do is

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:02.757
there are some that are retired.

00:48:02.824 --> 00:48:06.493
They come and have a lot of expertise
in really specific areas.

00:48:06.900 --> 00:48:10.301
They get on our boards for
the hospital board, the school district.

00:48:10.368 --> 00:48:13.336
So I mean the money, yes,
we really appreciate that.

00:48:13.403 --> 00:48:16.805
But they start to love the community
enough that they give their time.

00:48:16.872 --> 00:48:18.928
We were talking earlier about the divide.

00:48:18.995 --> 00:48:20.165
How about now?

00:48:20.945 --> 00:48:23.751
Is there an ideological divide
or not so much?

00:48:23.818 --> 00:48:25.528
-There is.
-There is.

00:48:25.595 --> 00:48:28.213
It's more kind of socioeconomic.

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:31.202
It's you know the haves, the have-nots.

00:48:31.269 --> 00:48:33.871
And you know the full-time working local

00:48:33.938 --> 00:48:36.447
or part-time working local I would say.

00:48:36.974 --> 00:48:40.932
You know the ski bum
or the ideal of being a ski bum.

00:48:40.999 --> 00:48:43.718
But it's really difficult.
But it always has been.

00:48:43.785 --> 00:48:48.121
People complain that they've got to have
three jobs to be able to pay rent here.

00:48:48.188 --> 00:48:50.971
But that was how it was
in the '70s and '80s too.

00:48:51.038 --> 00:48:53.959
When I lived in Tahoe
we all packed into a home.

00:48:54.026 --> 00:48:55.387
Yes. How many of you?

00:48:55.799 --> 00:48:57.474
There was a lot. Maybe six.

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:00.229
-For a two-bedroom probably.
-It was loud.

00:49:00.296 --> 00:49:02.179
That was how we were in college.

00:49:02.668 --> 00:49:04.168
-Was this a church before?

00:49:04.235 --> 00:49:05.498
-At one time it was.

00:49:05.565 --> 00:49:07.744
-And then it was the…
-Oak Street Inn.

00:49:07.811 --> 00:49:09.708
And before that it was a rec hall.

00:49:09.775 --> 00:49:12.325
Those are avalanche chutes
right behind there right?

00:49:12.392 --> 00:49:15.118
-Yeah. Coming off Ballard.
-Stunning. Ballard Mountain.

00:49:15.185 --> 00:49:17.937
This is hard to beat.
People talk big about Switzerland.

00:49:18.004 --> 00:49:20.010
I lived in Switzerland for a little bit.

00:49:20.077 --> 00:49:21.825
-What part?
-I lived in Verbier.

00:49:21.892 --> 00:49:22.885
Okay. Nice.

00:49:22.952 --> 00:49:24.905
Look. The mountains are extreme there

00:49:25.446 --> 00:49:29.138
but it doesn't have the
get on the open road in your pickup truck,

00:49:29.991 --> 00:49:32.593
you know, Western feel
up to it you know?

00:49:32.660 --> 00:49:35.178
I would say this is
way less flashy than Aspen.

00:49:35.245 --> 00:49:36.018
-Yes.

00:49:36.085 --> 00:49:38.770
A lot of people go to Aspen
or Vail to be seen.

00:49:39.248 --> 00:49:41.498
They come to Telluride to not be seen.

00:49:41.565 --> 00:49:42.448
Okay.

00:49:42.515 --> 00:49:44.103
Which is a huge difference.

00:49:44.578 --> 00:49:45.538
Telluride Fire?

00:49:45.605 --> 00:49:46.578
Heck yeah.

00:49:46.645 --> 00:49:48.138
How's it going out there?

00:49:48.205 --> 00:49:50.664
It's doing well.
What's up Mr. Ben? How you doing?

00:49:50.731 --> 00:49:52.907
-Not much. How about you?
-Doing well.

00:49:52.974 --> 00:49:55.461
-Got a painting job going on.
-Yeah.

00:49:55.528 --> 00:50:00.059
I didn't like the waste management green
so I switched it to bronze.

00:50:00.652 --> 00:50:04.321
That's what it sort of looked like.
One of those West End trash cans.

00:50:04.388 --> 00:50:07.516
So I was like I went with
a different bronze look.

00:50:07.583 --> 00:50:10.590
So where is the maiden voyage
gonna be for the new paint job?

00:50:10.657 --> 00:50:14.075
We're gonna go visit Brittany's family
up in northern Michigan.

00:50:14.142 --> 00:50:15.115
Oh nice.

00:50:15.182 --> 00:50:17.538
-Upper Peninsula?
-Yeah.

00:50:18.002 --> 00:50:21.057
And then we're gonna go up into Canada
over and then back down

00:50:21.124 --> 00:50:23.366
and then hit I-80 and just gun it.

00:50:24.016 --> 00:50:25.896
Perfect, and it'll be about July 4th.

00:50:25.963 --> 00:50:27.502
Exactly. Yeah.

00:50:27.569 --> 00:50:30.926
-Just in time for the fireworks.
-It's gonna be a lot of miles.

00:50:30.993 --> 00:50:31.876
Take care.

00:50:32.335 --> 00:50:35.435
So you guys had all the stories
from your relatives growing up?

00:50:35.517 --> 00:50:38.043
Yes. That's the part that was very fun.

00:50:38.110 --> 00:50:40.118
The wild and wooly days for sure.

00:50:40.185 --> 00:50:43.197
When was the last time
there were prostitutes and gunfights

00:50:43.264 --> 00:50:44.794
on the main drag there?

00:50:44.861 --> 00:50:46.978
Is that 100 years ago, 120 years ago?

00:50:47.045 --> 00:50:49.396
-I don't know.
Might have been a couple of years.

00:50:49.463 --> 00:50:51.470
Last year? Last winter?

00:50:51.537 --> 00:50:54.244
-The prostitutes never went away for sure.
-No.

00:50:54.311 --> 00:50:56.723
One of our family stories
is my great grandmother

00:50:56.790 --> 00:50:58.776
the house we saw down by the gondola,

00:50:58.843 --> 00:51:03.068
she did laundry for the girls
"on the line" they would say.

00:51:03.581 --> 00:51:07.441
And as I understand it
she never met any of them.

00:51:07.851 --> 00:51:11.541
They would come to her front door
with a basket, they would put it there,

00:51:11.608 --> 00:51:13.925
they would leave,
she would wash their laundry,

00:51:13.992 --> 00:51:17.642
fold it put it back, get their laundry,
and then she would give her money.

00:51:17.709 --> 00:51:19.062
She did that for years.

00:51:19.732 --> 00:51:21.771
And then my mom went to school here.

00:51:21.838 --> 00:51:24.414
And one of the madams here was Big Billie.

00:51:24.795 --> 00:51:29.093
And she said Big Billie would tell my mom
and her friends in high school

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:33.570
"We used to sell this until you high school
girls started giving it away."

00:51:33.637 --> 00:51:34.520
[giggles]

00:51:35.382 --> 00:51:38.737
Are there any people
like just long-term holdouts?

00:51:38.804 --> 00:51:41.931
They never really had any money
but they're real estate rich

00:51:41.998 --> 00:51:43.805
because they're living here but…

00:51:43.872 --> 00:51:45.598
-Oh there totally is.

00:51:45.665 --> 00:51:47.989
-There's some.
-That demographic hanging on.

00:51:48.056 --> 00:51:49.462
There's not a lot.

00:51:49.529 --> 00:51:53.981
Some from the mining era
and some from the early '70s era.

00:51:54.386 --> 00:51:57.224
Some of the hippies
that came in that you know are still…

00:51:57.291 --> 00:51:59.218
They got it then and they're holding.

00:51:59.285 --> 00:52:01.898
At some point in the latter '80s

00:52:01.965 --> 00:52:05.092
my dad… real estate
was really easy to get here in town

00:52:05.159 --> 00:52:07.640
and my dad said
"I'm gonna buy some lots in town."

00:52:07.707 --> 00:52:11.618
And my mom said don't you dare buy a lot.
I don't want anything in town.

00:52:11.685 --> 00:52:14.153
At that time they were 500 bucks a piece.

00:52:14.220 --> 00:52:15.103
-The lot?
-Yeah.

00:52:15.170 --> 00:52:17.817
My dad said
why did I listen to her that time?

00:52:18.710 --> 00:52:21.470
-Look at this street right now.
-It's great. Off-season.

00:52:21.537 --> 00:52:25.245
Because it was a mining town
and they had to turn teams and stuff around

00:52:25.312 --> 00:52:28.533
because you go gosh dang
that is a great large…

00:52:29.386 --> 00:52:31.709
-Oh teams of horses.
-Teams of horses. Yes.

00:52:31.776 --> 00:52:36.359
We actually did the first ever
in Telluride ski-joring a month ago now.

00:52:36.426 --> 00:52:37.790
-Look at that.
-Right?

00:52:40.352 --> 00:52:42.078
All right guys we got super lucky.

00:52:42.145 --> 00:52:46.566
Long-time locals,
they're gonna show us a cool part of town

00:52:46.633 --> 00:52:48.368
that they have their hands in.

00:52:48.435 --> 00:52:49.715
So we scored.

00:52:50.282 --> 00:52:52.245
What a beautiful place huh?

00:52:52.312 --> 00:52:54.841
And it's not the first time I've been here.

00:52:55.575 --> 00:52:58.309
I went to school at Fort Lewis College

00:52:59.135 --> 00:53:00.426
in Durango, Colorado.

00:53:01.095 --> 00:53:02.860
It's about two hours from here

00:53:03.256 --> 00:53:06.436
for two years in the late '90s.

00:53:06.863 --> 00:53:08.640
And I'd come here all the time

00:53:08.707 --> 00:53:12.769
because I had one friend who gave me
a ski pass 'cause he never came.

00:53:13.244 --> 00:53:15.579
Another friend his father had

00:53:16.070 --> 00:53:17.760
one of these monster homes

00:53:18.740 --> 00:53:20.183
up near the mountain.

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:21.981
And he said come any time.

00:53:22.048 --> 00:53:24.829
I figured out one winter
where I was leaving Durango,

00:53:25.289 --> 00:53:28.297
Thursday night snowboarding Telluride

00:53:29.335 --> 00:53:31.040
Friday, Saturday, Sunday, Monday,

00:53:31.107 --> 00:53:34.084
coming back, Monday night,
gonna school Tuesday,

00:53:34.151 --> 00:53:36.030
Thursday, and then off again.

00:53:36.097 --> 00:53:37.802
I spent a whole winter doing that.

00:53:37.869 --> 00:53:42.425
So a lot of good memories
ripping the terrain up there in the woods.

00:53:42.912 --> 00:53:44.773
We're only seeing the lower mountain.

00:53:44.840 --> 00:53:47.544
I don't think we're gonna
be able to get up there today

00:53:47.611 --> 00:53:49.028
but it goes back a ways.

00:53:49.095 --> 00:53:51.636
Really good vertical drop here
over 3,000 feet.

00:53:52.083 --> 00:53:54.996
My favorite ski resort in Colorado.

00:53:55.411 --> 00:53:57.924
So it feels awesome to be back.

00:54:07.335 --> 00:54:09.209
-This is so awesome up here.

00:54:09.276 --> 00:54:10.748
It's so amazing.

00:54:11.885 --> 00:54:14.532
-This was your family's property up here?
-Yes.

00:54:14.599 --> 00:54:16.700
My grandfather
started buying the property.

00:54:16.767 --> 00:54:19.532
We ended up with 5,000 acres
on deep Creek Mesa.

00:54:20.095 --> 00:54:23.579
This homestead is called the Hogg Ranch.

00:54:23.646 --> 00:54:24.717
H-O-G-G.

00:54:25.245 --> 00:54:26.833
However it was a dairy farm

00:54:27.545 --> 00:54:29.298
which were back in the mining days,

00:54:29.365 --> 00:54:32.584
several of the ranches
like the Schmidt Ranch over on Wilson Mesa,

00:54:32.651 --> 00:54:33.846
the Hogg Ranch here,

00:54:33.913 --> 00:54:37.758
they had the pasture and grew the hay
for the horses that worked in the mine.

00:54:37.825 --> 00:54:42.426
When the mine left then these people
had no economic drivers here

00:54:42.493 --> 00:54:45.317
so they were ready to get out.
So we bought from…

00:54:45.384 --> 00:54:50.738
My family never homesteaded anything
but we bought from 11 other homesteads

00:54:50.805 --> 00:54:55.261
of people that left between 1926 and 1950.

00:54:56.354 --> 00:54:57.442
-Oh, wow. This is…

00:54:57.509 --> 00:55:00.451
-The reason my family did this was because

00:55:00.518 --> 00:55:02.979
we were very typical agricultural people.

00:55:03.046 --> 00:55:06.917
Had real estate values that went up
so we could get more bank loans

00:55:06.984 --> 00:55:09.143
but our source of repayment
stayed the same.

00:55:09.210 --> 00:55:12.129
So many of us got into
a jeopardizing situation

00:55:12.196 --> 00:55:15.303
with too much cash going out
and not enough cash coming in

00:55:15.370 --> 00:55:18.123
and we were seriously gonna lose the ranch.

00:55:18.668 --> 00:55:21.130
We were in foreclosure in 1989

00:55:21.591 --> 00:55:24.914
everything for $1.4 million.
So 5,000 acres.

00:55:24.981 --> 00:55:28.277
-Whoa, whoa. This 5,000 acres in '89?

00:55:28.344 --> 00:55:31.096
In '89 was in foreclosure for $1.4 million.

00:55:31.970 --> 00:55:34.751
We were the ones,
the airport was on our property.

00:55:34.818 --> 00:55:37.719
We had a land lease with them
for $50,000 a year.

00:55:37.786 --> 00:55:40.846
And my dad which at that time
thought he'd hit like a home run

00:55:40.913 --> 00:55:42.992
that we were good for a long time.

00:55:43.059 --> 00:55:44.755
So anyway what happened was

00:55:44.822 --> 00:55:47.604
we were finally at a point
where we had to do something.

00:55:47.671 --> 00:55:50.053
I happened to be working
in the mountain village

00:55:50.120 --> 00:55:53.086
before the mountain village was a town.

00:55:53.153 --> 00:55:55.997
And for that development,
Mountain Village Inc.

00:55:56.064 --> 00:55:58.196
And I said, daddy we have to develop.

00:55:58.263 --> 00:56:00.474
And he said nope my dad bought property.

00:56:00.541 --> 00:56:04.103
I can't get rid of it.
That's that's kind of the last resort.

00:56:04.170 --> 00:56:08.229
Well we were finally in 1989
at a last resort and we had to subdivide.

00:56:08.888 --> 00:56:11.183
Luckily two men came to our rescue.

00:56:11.250 --> 00:56:13.056
Dick Depochter and John Horne.

00:56:13.123 --> 00:56:16.578
Both were very familiar
with development and Dick…

00:56:16.645 --> 00:56:18.717
They did this development right down here.

00:56:18.784 --> 00:56:19.978
Meadows at Deep Creek.

00:56:20.738 --> 00:56:24.713
My dad said I don't know
how to develop but I'm gonna have to.

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:27.986
So in an effort to lessen the sting,

00:56:28.053 --> 00:56:30.213
one of the things
that we did was daddy had…

00:56:30.280 --> 00:56:34.014
Daddy was the ultimate developer
and he had a say so.

00:56:34.081 --> 00:56:36.348
And everything that happened
or didn't happen.

00:56:36.415 --> 00:56:39.179
So the part that is cool
is it's got the Basque heritage

00:56:39.246 --> 00:56:40.854
which is his side of the family.

00:56:40.921 --> 00:56:44.074
All the road names are relatives
that are still that are here

00:56:44.141 --> 00:56:46.210
and some that are still in back in Spain.

00:56:46.277 --> 00:56:48.893
-We've been to the Basque country.
-Okay.

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:51.308
So that that lessened the hurt.

00:56:51.375 --> 00:56:53.188
I can remember daddy laughing.

00:56:53.808 --> 00:56:57.332
I always looked at a sheep pasture
and I didn't know it was this pretty

00:56:57.399 --> 00:57:01.579
until everyone started saying how beautiful
it was and I looked up and it is pretty.

00:57:01.646 --> 00:57:02.940
[Peter chuckles] Yeah.

00:57:04.771 --> 00:57:07.378
Oh wow. This is fantastic.

00:57:08.650 --> 00:57:10.186
So beautiful out here.

00:57:10.253 --> 00:57:12.968
-A cool spot to check out the whole region.

00:57:13.036 --> 00:57:16.872
Because from here you can look
in the town right downtown.

00:57:17.485 --> 00:57:19.932
You see the whole valley floor.

00:57:19.999 --> 00:57:24.617
That was actually condemned by the town
of Telluride about 20 years ago.

00:57:24.684 --> 00:57:29.938
So everything on the south side of
the highway going into town is open space.

00:57:32.062 --> 00:57:33.888
What an airport. Check this out.

00:57:34.575 --> 00:57:35.703
Plane comes in.

00:57:36.676 --> 00:57:38.488
Lands right on this Mesa here.

00:57:38.555 --> 00:57:42.332
-That's the highest commercial runway
in the United States.

00:57:42.956 --> 00:57:44.279
-What, around 9,000?

00:57:44.775 --> 00:57:47.128
It's right at about 9,100.

00:57:47.195 --> 00:57:49.031
-Looks like it just drops off.

00:57:49.475 --> 00:57:50.879
-It totally drops off.

00:57:50.946 --> 00:57:53.913
So it's totally like
flying off an aircraft carrier.

00:57:54.396 --> 00:57:56.961
-Denver Phoenix right?
Those are the two commercial.

00:57:57.028 --> 00:57:58.528
Denver Phoenix commercial.

00:57:58.595 --> 00:58:02.216
They're still working on some other ones
but that's it for right now.

00:58:02.283 --> 00:58:03.283
Bunch of private.

00:58:03.350 --> 00:58:05.168
Some of the people living in these homes.

00:58:05.235 --> 00:58:07.088
-They're flying private.
-All over the region.

00:58:07.155 --> 00:58:09.625
So you said Oprah's house
is over there somewhere.

00:58:09.692 --> 00:58:12.574
A new house over in the village.
Just finished it.

00:58:13.796 --> 00:58:15.923
This is called the Breckenridge Place.

00:58:16.406 --> 00:58:18.559
-See how there's two buildings out here?

00:58:18.626 --> 00:58:22.818
Back in the day the main house
was there and probably one bedroom.

00:58:22.885 --> 00:58:25.003
-Can we can we jump out there?
-Yeah.

00:58:28.565 --> 00:58:31.790
And then as the children would get married

00:58:31.857 --> 00:58:33.418
they would build their bedroom.

00:58:33.485 --> 00:58:34.868
-Oh no way.
-Yeah.

00:58:34.935 --> 00:58:36.400
So this was the main home.

00:58:36.467 --> 00:58:41.421
And this you will see in Butch Cassidy
and the Sundance Kid, the early days.

00:58:41.817 --> 00:58:43.051
You'll see this.

00:58:43.118 --> 00:58:44.583
Okay. And that's smart.

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:48.730
You have kids and just put them in little
shacks and get them out of the house.

00:58:48.797 --> 00:58:50.066
Well and they were older.

00:58:50.133 --> 00:58:53.953
They were actually probably
getting married just guessing.

00:58:54.020 --> 00:58:56.293
But what it did is
you figure back in the day

00:58:56.360 --> 00:58:58.978
all hands on deck
for any agricultural activity.

00:58:59.045 --> 00:58:59.928
-Yeah.

00:59:00.001 --> 00:59:02.795
Now it costs you money,
before it made you money.

00:59:02.862 --> 00:59:04.319
-Yes. 
-Big time.

00:59:04.775 --> 00:59:08.618
From the main ranch my sisters and I
would spend virtually all summer

00:59:08.685 --> 00:59:11.069
dragging stuff over here to play house

00:59:11.136 --> 00:59:13.767
and then spend the last part of summer
dragging stuff

00:59:13.834 --> 00:59:17.834
because it's about two miles away
where the old part of the ranch is.

00:59:18.164 --> 00:59:19.598
I have very fond memories.

00:59:19.665 --> 00:59:23.746
We were so excited when
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kids came

00:59:23.813 --> 00:59:28.348
because they were the ones that popped up
the porch because it had caved in.

00:59:28.415 --> 00:59:30.533
So that made it really nice housing.

00:59:36.608 --> 00:59:40.308
-Is that a home I'm looking at?
-Yeah. Just got finished.

00:59:40.375 --> 00:59:42.896
$1.4 million. All of this land.

00:59:42.963 --> 00:59:44.787
Now if you were to value it now

00:59:45.573 --> 00:59:46.960
We're in the hundreds…

00:59:47.027 --> 00:59:48.382
Probably. Yeah.

00:59:48.449 --> 00:59:51.115
Single family lots up here right now are

00:59:51.775 --> 00:59:54.859
around $2.5 million.

00:59:54.926 --> 00:59:57.506
There's a couple
a little bit lower like 1.6

00:59:57.573 --> 01:00:03.215
but like that house sold
for 7.6 a couple years ago.

01:00:03.694 --> 01:00:07.134
That one just sold for
$8 million last year.

01:00:08.453 --> 01:00:09.923
-Well that's a view.

01:00:09.990 --> 01:00:11.600
-Thanks for bringing me up here.
-Sure.

01:00:11.667 --> 01:00:14.881
'Cause I didn't think there are
too many fourth generation locals

01:00:14.948 --> 01:00:16.820
just walking around town.

01:00:16.887 --> 01:00:19.177
But you guys are both realtors?

01:00:19.244 --> 01:00:21.232
He's a real estate realtor.

01:00:21.299 --> 01:00:22.721
-You're a realtor?
-Yep.

01:00:22.788 --> 01:00:25.788
-I work for our family.
I do property management.

01:00:25.855 --> 01:00:27.764
-Okay. Scott what's your link?

01:00:27.831 --> 01:00:29.023
Wait. My link?

01:00:29.090 --> 01:00:33.598
Oh sorry. Your website, your link,
your social media, whatever you're using.

01:00:33.665 --> 01:00:37.165
-You're talking to a middle-aged guy.
-Dude you got to ask my daughter.

01:00:37.232 --> 01:00:38.272
She runs it.

01:00:38.339 --> 01:00:42.420
www.Telluride-home.com or
www.telluriderealestatebrokers.com.

01:00:43.347 --> 01:00:46.048
Is this nicer than Mountain Village
as far as values

01:00:46.115 --> 01:00:48.368
or it's just as expensive over there?

01:00:48.435 --> 01:00:51.488
-It's as, or more over there.

01:00:51.555 --> 01:00:55.377
One of the big things
that people are attracted to over there

01:00:55.444 --> 01:00:57.788
is being able to ski in, ski out.

01:00:57.855 --> 01:00:59.856
And so ski in, ski out,

01:00:59.923 --> 01:01:02.469
or ski accessible properties

01:01:02.536 --> 01:01:04.811
are another tier higher.

01:01:05.182 --> 01:01:06.228
-Okay.
-Yeah.

01:01:06.295 --> 01:01:07.178
Pretty cool.

01:01:07.245 --> 01:01:09.949
-What are the top going rates here?
$50 million?

01:01:10.016 --> 01:01:15.290
There was a house in Mountain Village
that sold in the last year for 39 million.

01:01:15.830 --> 01:01:21.078
There's a ranch up here
that was 300 and some odd acres.

01:01:21.145 --> 01:01:22.519
It sold for 39.

01:01:22.586 --> 01:01:24.292
-Is anyone up here full time?

01:01:24.750 --> 01:01:26.338
There's a lot of full time.

01:01:26.816 --> 01:01:29.665
Okay. They move in here
from all over the country or?

01:01:29.732 --> 01:01:30.848
All over. Yeah.

01:01:32.658 --> 01:01:33.985
[Peter] Thank you so much.

01:01:34.052 --> 01:01:36.533
Thank you.
I look forward to seeing your thing.

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:37.483
The YouTuber.

01:01:37.550 --> 01:01:39.808
Nice to meet you.
Safe travels. Stay in touch.

01:01:39.875 --> 01:01:42.592
You'll be cool with your kids
'cause you're on YouTube.

01:01:42.659 --> 01:01:46.023
I can hardly wait to be cool
'cause I drive them nuts. "Mom!"

01:01:46.558 --> 01:01:49.779
I usually just go to YouTube mechanic.

01:01:49.846 --> 01:01:51.546
-You're gonna be viral.
-I hope so.

01:01:51.613 --> 01:01:54.540
-I go to learn how to fix things.
-YouTube's amazing.

01:01:57.165 --> 01:01:58.923
Here we are in the mountain village.

01:01:58.990 --> 01:02:02.091
You can see the ski run
come right through the neighborhood.

01:02:02.158 --> 01:02:05.217
Ton of roads up here
with big homes, beautiful vistas.

01:02:06.185 --> 01:02:08.361
What a cool adventure today you guys.

01:02:08.830 --> 01:02:11.818
Such a cool part of the country,
cool part of the state.

01:02:11.885 --> 01:02:15.582
And like I always say
you can never label a place easily.

01:02:16.292 --> 01:02:17.783
Take Cortez this morning,

01:02:18.796 --> 01:02:20.478
ranching, mixed up town.

01:02:21.325 --> 01:02:24.207
Then we had the Ute Reservation
totally different.

01:02:24.675 --> 01:02:26.949
Then Rico, mining past.

01:02:27.411 --> 01:02:29.337
Spillover from Telluride.

01:02:30.005 --> 01:02:32.134
People looking for cheaper real estate.

01:02:32.660 --> 01:02:34.311
And then finally Telluride.

01:02:34.378 --> 01:02:36.931
World-class resort destination.

01:02:36.998 --> 01:02:38.231
Once a mining town.

01:02:39.161 --> 01:02:40.983
Totally switched into

01:02:41.434 --> 01:02:44.682
a ski resort destination place.

01:02:45.265 --> 01:02:47.935
Such a cool part of the country.

01:02:48.002 --> 01:02:49.531
And lastly, I'd like to say

01:02:50.088 --> 01:02:51.953
everyone we talked to today

01:02:52.826 --> 01:02:55.946
is loving where they're living.
I thought that was cool.

01:02:56.013 --> 01:02:58.594
Different culture, different temperatures.

01:02:58.944 --> 01:03:01.185
Totally different flora and fauna.

01:03:01.252 --> 01:03:03.767
Everyone we spoke with we got really lucky.

01:03:03.834 --> 01:03:05.331
Met a lot of great people.

01:03:05.398 --> 01:03:07.046
Such a cool country.

01:03:07.113 --> 01:03:08.172
Such a cool state.

01:03:08.895 --> 01:03:11.710
And Southwestern Colorado
is one of my favorites.

01:03:12.449 --> 01:03:15.421
All right you guys.
Thanks for coming along on that journey.

01:03:15.488 --> 01:03:16.599
Until the next one.

01:03:16.666 --> 01:03:18.108
[Western music]

